"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/65594","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2014-07-09","<p /> <p /> <p>The information requested is best provided in the following table:</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td colspan="4"><p><strong>% of Total DWP spend with SME's</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>Year</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Direct SME Spend</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Indirect SME Spend</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Total SME Spend</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>2010/11</strong></p></td><td><p>14.99%</p></td><td><p>1.95%</p></td><td><p><strong>16.94%</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>2011/12*</strong></p></td><td><p>11.11%</p></td><td><p>5.90%</p></td><td><p><strong>17.01%</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>2012/13**</strong></p></td><td><p>7.10%</p></td><td><p>8.90%</p></td><td><p><strong>16.00%</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>2013/14</strong></p></td><td><p>4.20%</p></td><td><p>11.28%</p></td><td><p><strong>15.48%</strong></p></td></tr></tbody></table><p><strong><sub>% figures have been rounded to 2 decimal places</sub></strong></p><p><strong><sub> </sub></strong></p><table><tbody><tr><td colspan="2"><p><strong>Targets for % Total spend with SME's </strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>Year</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Spend </strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>2014/15</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>16%</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>2015/16</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>18.5%</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>2016/17</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>21%</strong></p></td></tr></tbody></table><p><strong> </strong></p><p>With around 78% of the department's contract expenditure due to be re-tendered in the next 4 years, the Department will undertake a number of activities designed to encourage SME's to engage with our procurement exercises.</p>","Hemel Hempstead","Mike Penning",,"2014-07-09T10:43:24.8075161Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/65594/answer","Biography information for Sir Mike Penning","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/65594/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/65594/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2014-07-02","Procurement","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what proportion of his Department's procurement expenditure was awarded to small and medium-sized enterprises in (a) direct procurement and (b) indirect procurement spend in (i) 2010, (ii) 2011, (iii) 2012 and (iv) 2013; and what the projected proportion is for (A) 2014, (B) 2015 and (C) 2016.","false","Biography information for Rachel Reeves","Leeds West","Rachel Reeves","203787"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/65595","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2014-07-07","<p /> <p /> <p> </p><p /> <p>(a) The housing benefit bill was expected to rise above Â£25 billion in 2014/15 (Â£15 billion for the social rented sector alone) prior to the introduction of the removal of the spare room subsidy.</p><p> </p><p>The Department estimated the policy would achieve savings of Â£490 million in 2013/14, Â£525 million in 2014/15 and Â£560 million in 2015/16.</p><p> </p><p>(b) to (d)</p><p> </p><p>The policy to remove the spare room subsidy introduces not only parity of treatment between the private and social rented sectors, but encourages more effective use of social housing stock. It has reduced the number of households who under-occupy their properties, which has freed up larger homes for those currently on the social housing waiting list who are living in overcrowded conditions. It also encourages social providers to take account of local needs and demographic trends when allocating properties and developing their building programmes. Levels of homelessness acceptances in England have reduced 7 per cent in the last quarter compared to the same period in the previous year. This is 65 per cent lower than the peak in 2003.</p><p>The effects of the policy are being monitored and evaluated over a two-year period from April 2013. Initial findings will be published before recess and the final report in late 2015.</p><p> </p>","Wirral West","Esther McVey",,"2014-07-07T16:14:44.0862766Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/65595/answer","Biography information for Esther McVey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/65595/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/65595/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2014-07-02","Housing Benefit: Social Rented Housing","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what assessment he has made of the effects of the introduction of the under-occupancy penalty on (a) the total housing benefit bill, (b) overcrowding, (c) homelessness and (d) housing mobility.","false","Biography information for Mr Philip Hollobone","Kettering","Mr Philip Hollobone","203739"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/65596","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2014-07-09","<p /> <p /> <p>The information is not held centrally. We estimate that developing an appropriate methodology and quality assuring the analysis would exceed disproportionate cost limits.</p><p><strong> </strong></p>","Wirral West","Esther McVey",,"2014-07-09T14:13:35.5866595Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/65596/answer","Biography information for Esther McVey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/65596/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/65596/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2014-07-02","New Enterprise Allowance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how many (a) women's and (b) men's business plans which were approved received a weekly allowance for 26 weeks of a total of Â£1,274 as part of the new enterprise allowance.","false","Biography information for Gloria De Piero","Ashfield","Gloria De Piero","203824"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/65597","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2014-07-09","<p /> <p /> <p>The numbers of recipients of New Enterprise Allowance financial support for whom we have a record of at least one claim for Access to Work, Disability Living Allowance, Incapacity Benefit or Employment Support Allowance are shown in the table below</p><p> </p><p><strong>NEA participants with at least one previous claim for Access to Work (AtW), Disability Living Allowance (</strong><strong>DLA</strong><strong>), Incapacity Benefit (IB) and/or Employment Support Allowance (</strong><strong>ESA</strong><strong>) by gender</strong></p><table><tbody><tr><td><p><strong> </strong></p></td><td><p><strong>AtW</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>DLA</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>ESA</strong><strong>/IB</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>Male</strong></p></td><td><p>100</p></td><td><p>700</p></td><td><p>8,500</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>Female</strong></p></td><td><p>100</p></td><td><p>400</p></td><td><p>4,000</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>Total</strong></p></td><td><p>200</p></td><td><p>1,200</p></td><td><p>12,500</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p>Notes:</p><p>1. Figures rounded to nearest 100. Totals may not sum due to rounding</p><p>2. Figures include all claims for AtW and ESA and all live claims since 28<sup>th</sup> June 1999 for IB and DLA</p><p>3. Claimants are counted for each of the benefits they have claimed previously, e.g. someone who has claimed DLA and IB is counted in both columns</p><p>4. Claimants who have previously claimed both ESA and IB are only counted once in the ESA/IB column</p><p>5. DLA can be claimed at the same time as NEA. Figures include NEA participants whose DLA claim continues whilst also receiving NEA financial support</p><p>6. Access to Work is available to NEA participants. Figures for AtW include those who claimed AtW support within 6 months of starting NEA financial support</p>","Wirral West","Esther McVey",,"2014-07-09T14:24:00.4857956Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/65597/answer","Biography information for Esther McVey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/65597/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/65597/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2014-07-02","New Enterprise Allowance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how many of the recipients of the new enterprise allowance who previously claimed (a) access to work benefits, (b) disability living allowance and (c) incapacity benefit were (i) male and (ii) female.","false","Biography information for Gloria De Piero","Ashfield","Gloria De Piero","203822"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/65598","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2014-07-09","<p /> <p /> <p>Official Statistics on the numbers of New Enterprise Allowance mentoring starts and financial support starts are published quarterly and can be accessed via the link below.</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/pre-work-programme-and-get-britain-working#new-enterprise-allowance-statistics" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/pre-work-programme-and-get-britain-working#new-enterprise-allowance-statistics</a></p><p> </p><p>These statistics include a breakdown of starts by gender.</p>","Wirral West","Esther McVey",,"2014-07-09T14:04:02.82272Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/65598/answer","Biography information for Esther McVey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/65598/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/65598/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2014-07-02","New Enterprise Allowance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how many (a) women and (b) men are recipients of the new enterprise allowance.","false","Biography information for Gloria De Piero","Ashfield","Gloria De Piero","203827"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/65599","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2014-07-07","<p /> <p /> <p>We keep the time taken to process claims under constant review and are absolutely committed to improving performance. We accept that the delays faced by some people are unacceptable, and we are committed to putting that right. By the Autumn, we expect no one to be waiting for an assessment for longer than 26 weeks and by the end of the year, we expect no one will be waiting longer than 16 weeks.</p>","Hemel Hempstead","Mike Penning",,"2014-07-07T15:21:34.7592963Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/65599/answer","Biography information for Sir Mike Penning","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/65599/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/65599/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2014-07-02","Personal Independence Payment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what forecast his Department has made of the length of time each part of the claims process for personal independence payment (PIP) up to provision of accurate and targeted assessments will take; and what guidance his Department uses for a reasonable amount of time for an individual to wait for an accurate targeted assessment for PIP.","false","Biography information for Derek Twigg","Halton","Derek Twigg","203706"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/65600","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2014-07-08","<p /> <p /> <p>We are continuously looking at ways to increase the number of decisions made and to improve the claims process.</p><p> </p><p>We are working closely with both assessment providers as part of our plans to speed up the end to end claimant journey. We have introduced improvements in communications to claimants about the type of evidence they can supply to speed up their claim and we are taking action to support the assessment providers in clearing backlogs of work.</p>","Hemel Hempstead","Mike Penning",,"2014-07-08T14:14:35.5403675Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/65600/answer","Biography information for Sir Mike Penning","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/65600/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/65600/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2014-07-02","Personal Independence Payment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what steps his Department has taken to deal with backlogs in personal independence payments.","false","Biography information for Katy Clark","North Ayrshire and Arran","Katy Clark","203681"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/65601","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2014-07-08","<p>By the Autumn, we expect no one to be waiting for an assessment for longer than 26 weeks and by the end of the year, we expect no one will be waiting longer than 16 weeks.</p>","Hemel Hempstead","Mike Penning",,"2014-07-08T14:23:46.332717Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/65601/answer","Biography information for Sir Mike Penning","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/65601/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/65601/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2014-07-02","Personal Independence Payment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, when he expects personal independence payment backlogs to be cleared.","false","Biography information for Katy Clark","North Ayrshire and Arran","Katy Clark","203682"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/65602","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2014-07-08","<p /> <p /> <p>DWP Operations has a large number of employees at the decision maker grade (EO) and we are constantly reviewing our plans to ensure that we have the right number of people to deliver all of our services.</p><p><strong> </strong></p>","Hemel Hempstead","Mike Penning",,"2014-07-08T14:07:13.3650908Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/65602/answer","Biography information for Sir Mike Penning","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/65602/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/65602/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2014-07-02","Personal Independence Payment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, if he will recruit additional staff to help clear personal independence payment backlogs.","false","Biography information for Katy Clark","North Ayrshire and Arran","Katy Clark","203683"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/65603","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2014-07-08","<p> </p><p>The information requested is shown in the tables below.</p><p> </p><p>Further benefit expenditure can be found at the following URL:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/benefit-expenditure-tables" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/benefit-expenditure-tables</a></p><p> </p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p>Housing Benefit expenditure, Â£ million, nominal</p></td><td><p>2008/09</p></td><td><p>2009/10</p></td><td><p>2010/11</p></td><td><p>2011/12</p></td><td><p>2012/13</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Cannock Chase</p></td><td><p>19.1</p></td><td><p>23.4</p></td><td><p>25.5</p></td><td><p>27.0</p></td><td><p>28.0</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Staffordshire</p></td><td><p>132.5</p></td><td><p>159.5</p></td><td><p>171.5</p></td><td><p>181.8</p></td><td><p>192.1</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p> </p><p>Source: Local Authority subsidy returns.</p><p> </p>","Thornbury and Yate","Steve Webb",,"2014-07-08T15:21:08.2131214Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/65603/answer","Biography information for Steve Webb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/65603/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/65603/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2014-07-02","Housing Benefit: Staffordshire","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how much was spent on housing benefit in (a) Cannock Chase and (b) Staffordshire in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Mr Aidan Burley","Cannock Chase","Mr Aidan Burley","203634"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/65604","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2014-07-07","<p /> <p>The series of behaviour trials completed later than expected, in May 2014. Now that the trials are completed, a full evaluation is underway. Once the evaluation has concluded, we will share the findings in accordance with the undertakings we gave to the Select Committee, in October 2013. We will incorporate any learning from the successful trials into our approach to tackle and prevent the build-up of arrears.</p>","Thornbury and Yate","Steve Webb",,"2014-07-07T13:46:00.9045463Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/65604/answer","Biography information for Steve Webb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/65604/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/65604/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2014-07-02","Children: Maintenance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, with reference to the written evidence from his Department to the Work and Pensions Committee of 20 October 2013 on child maintenance reform, when he will publish initial findings from the series of behaviour change trials undertaken by his Department to test different interventions aimed at addressing the barriers that prevent parents making regular payments of child maintenance.","false","Biography information for Sheila Gilmore","Edinburgh East","Sheila Gilmore","203665"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/65605","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2014-07-07","<p>We are exploring bringing into force powers laid out in the Child Maintenance and Other Payments Act 2008, providing for the disclosure of payment information to credit reference agencies. This would be subject to a public consultation before any regulations were laid in Parliament.</p>","Thornbury and Yate","Steve Webb",,"2014-07-07T13:33:55.5007575Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/65605/answer","Biography information for Steve Webb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/65605/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/65605/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2014-07-02","Children: Maintenance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, when he will bring into force section 40 of the Child Maintenance and Other Payments Act 2008.","false","Biography information for Sheila Gilmore","Edinburgh East","Sheila Gilmore","203664"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/65606","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2014-07-09","There are no formal targets in place for increasing the number of women who participate in the New Enterprise Allowance scheme. Latest statistics show that since the launch of NEA in 2011 to the end of March 2014, there were 46,000 allowance claims, of which 15,720 were from women. The weekly allowance is payable when the participant closes their claim to benefits and commences trading. The rate of take up of NEA by women is approximately one third of the total. This is consistent with the proportion of women claiming Jobseeker's Allowance (the benefit claimed by the majority of NEA participants), demonstrating the success of the scheme in attracting all groups to access this support.","Wirral West","Esther McVey",,"2014-07-09T15:14:52.2317351Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/65606/answer","Biography information for Esther McVey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/65606/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/65606/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2014-07-02","New Enterprise Allowance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what targets there are on increasing the number of women receiving the new enterprise allowance; and what progress has been made on these targets in the last year.","false","Biography information for Gloria De Piero","Ashfield","Gloria De Piero","203807"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/65607","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2014-07-09","<p /> <p /> <p>The Department has made an assessment of the number of New Enterprise Allowance participants returning to any out-of-work benefit in the following published analysis. This suggests that 78% of people who started drawing the New Enterprise Allowance remained off benefit continuously for 12 months.</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/225167/NEA_benefit_status_ad-hoc_v3.pdf" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/225167/NEA_benefit_status_ad-hoc_v3.pdf</a></p><p> </p><p>The analysis is not available by type of benefit or by gender.</p><p><strong> </strong></p>","Wirral West","Esther McVey",,"2014-07-09T14:44:47.8088476Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/65607/answer","Biography information for Esther McVey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/65607/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/65607/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2014-07-02","New Enterprise Allowance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how many people who received the new enterprise allowance have since reclaimed (a) jobseeker's allowance, (b) income support as a lone parent and (c) employment and support allowance; and how many of these were (i) women and (ii) men.","false","Biography information for Gloria De Piero","Ashfield","Gloria De Piero","203806"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/65608","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2014-07-07","<p /> <p /> <p>I refer the hon. Member to the written answer I gave the hon. Member for Lewisham East (Heidi Alexander), on 2 July 2014, <em>Official Report, </em>column 641W.</p><p><strong> </strong></p><p><strong> </strong></p>","Hemel Hempstead","Mike Penning",,"2014-07-07T16:48:14.6981861Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/65608/answer","Biography information for Sir Mike Penning","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/65608/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/65608/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2014-07-02","Personal Independence Payment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what steps his Department is taking to better identify personal independence payment claimaints who could be assessed solely on the basis of written evidence and without the need for face-to-face assessments.","false","Biography information for Derek Twigg","Halton","Derek Twigg","203696"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/65609","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2014-07-07","<p /> <p /> <p>All jobseeker's are assessed at the beginning of their claim to Jobseeker's Allowance for potential skills needs that are a barrier to them finding work. Where a skills need is identified, claimants are referred to courses.</p><p> </p><p>This Government is committed to ensuring jobseekers have the skills they need to get into work. In 2012/13 171,100 young people aged 19-24 and claiming benefit started a learning course, an increase of 30% over 2011/12.</p><p><strong> </strong></p>","Wirral West","Esther McVey",,"2014-07-07T14:46:34.9502598Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/65609/answer","Biography information for Esther McVey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/65609/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/65609/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2014-07-02","Jobseeker's Allowance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, pursuant to the Answer of 30 June 2014, Official Report, column 431W, on jobseeker's allowance, how many jobseekers aged (a) between 18 and 21, (b) 22 and 24 and (c) 25 years and over were assessed for potential skills needs at the beginning of their claim to jobseeker's allowance in the most recent year for which data is available; and how many jobseekers in each category were assessed as having a skills need.","false","Biography information for Stephen Timms","East Ham","Stephen Timms","203725"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/65610","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2014-07-07","<p /> <p>The Government published a detailed impact assessment in December 2012 to accompany the laying of the universal credit regulations that came into force in April 2013. There are no current plans to publish an update.</p>","Wirral West","Esther McVey",,"2014-07-07T14:50:42.6234525Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/65610/answer","Biography information for Esther McVey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/65610/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/65610/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2014-07-02","Universal Credit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, on what date he plans to publish the revised impact assessment for universal credit.","false","Biography information for Stephen Timms","East Ham","Stephen Timms","203726"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/65611","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2014-07-07","<p /> <p /> <p>Unfortunately, the information requested is not routinely collected by the Department and is therefore unavailable at this time.</p><p> </p>","Hemel Hempstead","Mike Penning",,"2014-07-07T15:25:53.3835519Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/65611/answer","Biography information for Sir Mike Penning","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/65611/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/65611/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2014-07-02","Procurement","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what proportion of his Department's contracts were awarded to small and medium- sized enterprises in (a) direct procurement spend and (b) indirect procurement spend in (i) 2010, (ii) 2011, (iii) 2012 and (iv) 2013; and what the projected proportion is for (A) 2014, (B) 2015 and (C) 2016.","false","Biography information for Rachel Reeves","Leeds West","Rachel Reeves","203717"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/65612","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2014-07-08","<p /> <p /> <p>Personal independence payment (PIP) includes a more objective assessment process than for Disability living allowance (DLA), with a face-to-face consultation for most applicants, that enables a more accurate and consistent assessment of individual need. Unlike DLA, eligibility for PIP is not assessed on the type of health condition or impairment an individual may have.</p>","Hemel Hempstead","Mike Penning",,"2014-07-08T14:19:38.1891727Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/65612/answer","Biography information for Sir Mike Penning","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/65612/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/65612/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2014-07-02","Personal Independence Payment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what comparative assessment he has made of the methods used to assess personal independence payment claims with the methods used to assess disability living allowance claims.","false","Biography information for Katy Clark","North Ayrshire and Arran","Katy Clark","203684"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/65613","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2014-07-07","<p> </p><p> </p><p>The Department spent Â£186m on IT, development and implementation for Universal Credit in 2013-14, against the previously forecast Â£401m.</p><p> </p><p>The forecast for 2014-15 is currently Â£316m against the previous forecast of Â£317m</p><p> </p><p>This forecast is subject to change due to further refinements of requirements and on-going commercial discussions. Plans continue to be developed to support rollout of UC within budget.</p>","Wirral West","Esther McVey",,"2014-07-07T16:26:47.3507077Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/65613/answer","Biography information for Esther McVey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/65613/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/65613/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2014-07-02","Universal Credit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, pursuant to the Answer of 11 June 2014, Official Report, column 282W, on universal credit, how much his Department spent on IT development and implementation for universal credit in 2013-14; and how much it expects to spend on such development and implementation in 2014-15.","false","Biography information for Stephen Timms","East Ham","Stephen Timms","203724"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/65614","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2014-07-07","<p /> <p /> <p>Most claimants to personal independence payment (PIP) will already be receiving some element of financial support to meet day-to-day living expenses, for example through earnings or through receipt of income maintenance benefits such as employment and support allowance. No successful new claimant to PIP will lose out financially as claims will be backdated. Additionally, disability living allowance (DLA) claimants claiming PIP continue to receive their DLA while the PIP claim is being assessed. <br></p>","Hemel Hempstead","Mike Penning",,"2014-07-07T15:20:30.6673668Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/65614/answer","Biography information for Sir Mike Penning","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/65614/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/65614/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2014-07-02","Personal Independence Payment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, whether disabled people who go into debt because of long delays in processing their personal independence payment claims will be able to receive assistance from the Government to help pay off the interest on their debts.","false","Biography information for Mr Roger Godsiff","Birmingham, Hall Green","Mr Roger Godsiff","203731"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/65615","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2014-07-07","<p /> <p /> <p>Unfortunately, the information requested is not routinely collected by the Department and is therefore unavailable at this time.</p>","Hemel Hempstead","Mike Penning",,"2014-07-07T14:26:52.8458943Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/65615/answer","Biography information for Sir Mike Penning","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/65615/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/65615/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2014-07-02","Procurement","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how of his Department's contracts were awarded to small and medium sized enterprises in (a) direct procurement spend and (b) indirect procurement spend in (i) 2010, (ii) 2011, (iii) 2012 and (iv) 2013; and what the projected number is for (A) 2014, (B) 2015 and (C) 2016.","false","Biography information for Rachel Reeves","Leeds West","Rachel Reeves","203721"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/65616","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2014-07-07","<p /> <p /> <p>The number of apprentices employed in DWP for the years asked for is as follows:</p><p> </p><p>a) 2010 - 0</p><p>b) 2011 - 109</p><p>c) 2012 - 243</p><p>d) 2013 - 273</p><p>e) 2014 - 316</p><p> </p><p>the anticipated number of apprentices to be employed in DWP in the future years asked for is as follows:</p><p> </p><p>i) 2015 - 330</p><p>ii) 2016 - 350</p><p><strong> </strong></p>","Hemel Hempstead","Mike Penning",,"2014-07-07T16:39:22.6391192Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/65616/answer","Biography information for Sir Mike Penning","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/65616/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/65616/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2014-07-02","Apprentices","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how many apprenticeships his Department and its agencies employed in (a) 2010, (b) 2011, (c) 2012, (d) 2013 and (e) 2014; and how many he expects to employ in (i) 2015 and (ii) 2016.","false","Biography information for Rachel Reeves","Leeds West","Rachel Reeves","203722"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/65617","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2014-07-07","<p /> <p /> <p>We keep the time taken to process claims under constant review and are absolutely committed to improving performance. We are already seeing improvements to our processes and will continue to work to further reduce delays and backlogs.</p><p><strong> </strong></p>","Hemel Hempstead","Mike Penning",,"2014-07-07T16:51:28.3212226Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/65617/answer","Biography information for Sir Mike Penning","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/65617/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/65617/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2014-07-02","Personal Independence Payment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, whether his Department has conducted an impact assessment of the effects of the time taken to resolve claims for personal independence payments on claimants.","false","Biography information for Derek Twigg","Halton","Derek Twigg","203698"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/65618","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2014-07-07","<p /> <p /> <p>As soon as I became aware of the length of time it was taking some Special Rules cases to be processed I took action to reduce the timescales and introduced:</p><p> </p><p>â¢ A dedicated phone service with specially trained staff;</p><p> </p><p>â¢ An electronic transfer of information between a claimant's health professional, DWP and assessment providers.</p><p> </p><p>â¢ a trial of a new process to enable decisions to be made in-house with support from health care professionals</p><p> </p><p>I am pleased to say that we are now seeing improvements to clearance times for claims from terminally ill people.</p><p> </p><p>We have acknowledged that claims under our normal rules are currently taking too long. We are absolutely committed to improving performance â ours and that of the assessment providers. We are already seeing improvements to our processes and will continue to work to further reduce delays and backlogs.</p><p> </p><p>By the Autumn, we expect no one to be waiting for an assessment for longer than 26 weeks and by the end of the year, we expect no one will be waiting longer than 16 weeks.<strong>âââââ</strong></p>","Hemel Hempstead","Mike Penning",,"2014-07-07T16:45:30.7597195Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/65618/answer","Biography information for Sir Mike Penning","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/65618/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/65618/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2014-07-02","Personal Independence Payment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what steps his Department took to reduce delays to personal independence payment (PIP) special rules claims; how long it took to resolve those delays; what steps he plans to take to reduce delays to PIP claims in the normal rules; and what estimate he has made of the time that will be taken to reduce those delays.","false","Biography information for Derek Twigg","Halton","Derek Twigg","203699"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/65619","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2014-07-07","<p /> <p /> <p>Information on how many new claims were paid in April 2014 for (a) Jobseeker's Allowance (JSA), (b) Employment and Support Allowance (ESA), (c) Income Support (IS), (d) Housing Benefit (HB) and (e) Universal Credit (UC) is not readily available and to provide it would incur disproportionate cost.</p><p> </p><p>Statistics on the number of JSA claimants who started a new claim in April 2014 can be found at:</p><p> </p><p><a href="http://www.nomisweb.co.uk/" target="_blank">http://www.nomisweb.co.uk/</a></p><p> </p><p>Guidance for users can be found at:</p><p> </p><p><a href="http://www.nomisweb.co.uk/home/newuser.asp" target="_blank">http://www.nomisweb.co.uk/home/newuser.asp</a></p><p> </p><p>Statistics on the number of ESA and IS claimants who started a new claim, by the number of previous claims on this benefit, up to and including November 2013 can be found at:</p><p> </p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/dwp-statistics-tabulation-tool" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/dwp-statistics-tabulation-tool</a></p><p> </p><p>Guidance for users is available at:</p><p> </p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/dwp-tabulation-tool-guidance" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/dwp-tabulation-tool-guidance</a></p><p> </p><p>Statistics covering the period March 2014 to May 2014 are due to be published on 12 November 2014</p><p><strong> </strong></p><p>Statistics on the number of Universal Credit (UC) claimants who started a new claim up to and including March 2014 can be found at:</p><p><strong> </strong></p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/universal-credit-statistics" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/universal-credit-statistics</a></p><p><strong> </strong></p><p>Statistics for April 2014 are due to be published on 16 July 2014</p><p><strong> </strong></p>","Wirral West","Esther McVey",,"2014-07-07T15:48:17.3945414Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/65619/answer","Biography information for Esther McVey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/65619/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/65619/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2014-07-02","Social Security Benefits","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how many new claims were paid in April 2014 for (a) jobseeker's allowance, (b) employment and support allowance, (c) income support, (d) housing benefit and (e) universal credit.","false","Biography information for Stephen Timms","East Ham","Stephen Timms","203728"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/65623","Attorney General","false","2014-07-08","<p>In 2010-11, the baseline year for the current Comprehensive Spending Review Period, the Crown Prosecution Service's (CPS) gross resource expenditure was Â£684,725,000.</p><p>The department is on target to meet its cost reduction plans through to 2015-16 and in 2013-14 the uncertified Annual Accounts report gross resource expenditure of Â£616,342,000, a reduction of Â£68,383,000, or 10%, in cash terms.</p><p> </p>","Beaconsfield","Mr Dominic Grieve",,"2014-07-08T14:21:37.3920214Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/65623/answer","Biography information for Mr Dominic Grieve","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/65623/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/65623/answer",,,,,"88","Attorney General","Attorney General","2014-07-02","Crown Prosecution Service","1","House of Commons","To ask the Attorney General, what progress the Crown Prosecution Service has made in reducing costs.","false","Biography information for Debbie Abrahams","Oldham East and Saddleworth","Debbie Abrahams","904723"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/65779","Ministry of Justice","false","2014-07-08","<p>A life sentence is mandatory for murder and there is statutory guidance to the courts in determining the appropriate minimum term when sentencing. Manslaughter has a maximum penalty of life imprisonment and, within that maximum penalty, it is necessary that judges are able to sentence according to all the factors in each case. There is no sentencing guideline on unlawful act manslaughter but there is case law to assist the courts.</p><p> </p><p>Following the comments of the Attorney General and the Court of Appeal in the case of Lewis Gill, the Government considers that clarification of sentencing in manslaughter cases would assist the courts in these difficult cases and be helpful to the public. The Secretary of State for Justice therefore wrote to Lord Justice Treacy, the Chair of the Sentencing Council, on 8 May 2014 to make a formal request that the Council gives consideration to producing guidance on the sentencing of these cases.</p><p> </p>","Kenilworth and Southam","Jeremy Wright",,"2014-07-08T16:49:28.1867166Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/65779/answer","Biography information for Jeremy Wright","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/65779/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/65779/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2014-07-02","Homicide: Sentencing","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what steps he is taking to review sentences given for (a) murder and (b) manslaughter where the offence was a one-punch killing.","false","Biography information for Craig Whittaker","Calder Valley","Craig Whittaker","904724"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66226","Attorney General","false","2014-07-08","<p>The Attorney General and I meet regularly with the Director of Service Prosecutions and discuss casework issues at these meetings. This includes the prosecution of rape and other sexual offences.</p>","North East Hertfordshire","Oliver Heald",,"2014-07-08T14:17:46.225497Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66226/answer","Biography information for Sir Oliver Heald","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66226/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66226/answer",,,,,"88","Attorney General","Attorney General","2014-07-02","Armed Forces: Sexual Offences","1","House of Commons","To ask the Attorney General, what recent discussions he has had with the Director of the Services Prosecution Authority about its effectiveness in prosecuting rape and other sexual offences in the armed forces in the UK and overseas.","false","Biography information for Andrew Gwynne","Denton and Reddish","Andrew Gwynne","904727"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66227","Deputy Prime Minister","false","2014-07-08","<p>I have regular discussions with ministerial colleagues on devolution and decentralisation which have culminated in the government's announcement of one of the biggest steps in decentralisation in a generation. Yesterday we announced individual deals with all 39 local Enterprise Partnerships with a total investment of more than Â£6bn. The growth deal heralds a new era for the Humber economy.</p><p> </p>","Tunbridge Wells","Greg Clark",,"2014-07-08T15:17:13.4032963Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66227/answer","Biography information for Greg Clark","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66227/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66227/answer",,,,,"58","Deputy Prime Minister","Deputy Prime Minister","2014-07-02","Local Government: Yorkshire and the Humber","1","House of Commons","To ask the Deputy Prime Minister, what recent discussions he has had with his ministerial colleagues on further devolution of power from Westminster and Whitehall to the Humber region.","false","Biography information for Martin Vickers","Cleethorpes","Martin Vickers","904720"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66228","Deputy Prime Minister","false","2014-07-08","<p>As I announced yesterday, the Government is awarding the South East LEP a total of Â£6.8m to help develop a Growth Hub in Kent and Medway which will simplify and better co-ordinate the range of services delivered to businesses in the area.</p><p>The Government has also funded the TIGER RGF programme which has been allocated Â£20m to support businesses seeking finance for growth in north Kent and Thurrock, Essex. The scheme extends beyond Medway but the largest concentration of eligible employers is in the Medway area.</p><p> </p>","Tunbridge Wells","Greg Clark",,"2014-07-08T15:25:31.8975316Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66228/answer","Biography information for Greg Clark","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66228/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66228/answer",,,,,"58","Deputy Prime Minister","Deputy Prime Minister","2014-07-02","Business: Medway","1","House of Commons","To ask the Deputy Prime Minister, what support the Government is giving to business growth opportunities in Medway.","false","Biography information for Rehman Chishti","Gillingham and Rainham","Rehman Chishti","904718"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66229","Deputy Prime Minister","false","2014-07-08","<p>I met with the Coventry and Warwickshire LEP on 24 March to sign the City Deal, and we have now agreed a Growth Deal with Coventry and Warwickshire LEP.</p><p>The deal has secured Â£74m from the Government's Local Growth Fund to support economic growth in the area â with nearly Â£14m of new funding confirmed for 2015/16. This includes projects such as a new grow-on space for innovative businesses at Ansty Park near Rugby.</p><p> </p>","Tunbridge Wells","Greg Clark",,"2014-07-08T15:28:31.4864109Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66229/answer","Biography information for Greg Clark","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66229/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66229/answer",,,,,"58","Deputy Prime Minister","Deputy Prime Minister","2014-07-02","Local Government: Warwickshire","1","House of Commons","To ask the Deputy Prime Minister, what discussions has he had with the Coventry and Warwickshire Local Enterprise Partnership on devolving powers and responsibilities from central government.","false","Biography information for Mark Pawsey","Rugby","Mark Pawsey","904716"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66230","Deputy Prime Minister","false","2014-07-08","<p>Cities and Local Enterprise Partnerships are making excellent progress in implementing their City Deals.</p><p>The Coventry and Warwickshire City Deal was signed on 12 December 2013 and the Skills for Growth pilot has already registered 37 graduates, exceeding its targets.</p><p> </p>","Tunbridge Wells","Greg Clark",,"2014-07-08T15:16:07.5834383Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66230/answer","Biography information for Greg Clark","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66230/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66230/answer",,,,,"58","Deputy Prime Minister","Deputy Prime Minister","2014-07-02","Local Government: Urban Areas","1","House of Commons","To ask the Deputy Prime Minister, what recent assessment he has made of how City Deals are working.","false","Biography information for Chris White","Warwick and Leamington","Chris White","904722"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66231","Deputy Prime Minister","false","2014-07-08","<p>The Government's intention to bring forward a recall Bill in this session was announced in the Queen's speech on 4 June.</p><p> </p>","Tunbridge Wells","Greg Clark",,"2014-07-08T15:29:59.2920876Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66231/answer","Biography information for Greg Clark","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66231/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66231/answer",,,,,"58","Deputy Prime Minister","Deputy Prime Minister","2014-07-02","Members: Conduct","1","House of Commons","To ask the Deputy Prime Minister, when he plans to bring forward legislative proposals on the recall of hon. Members.","false","Biography information for David Hanson","Delyn","Mr David Hanson","904715"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66232","Deputy Prime Minister","false","2014-07-08","<p>Yesterday I announced that we have concluded a growth deal with the Nottingham and Nottinghamshire LEP, which includes Newark.</p><p>The deal involves Â£172 million of Government investment in the Nottinghamshire and Derbyshire area, a substantial commitment that will benefit businesses in Newark and throughout Nottinghamshire. A significant part of this investment will go towards a new Southern Link Road in Newark, which will help to alleviate congestion in the area and create 2,400 jobs.</p><p> </p>","Tunbridge Wells","Greg Clark",,"2014-07-08T15:26:45.8358456Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66232/answer","Biography information for Greg Clark","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66232/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66232/answer",,,,,"58","Deputy Prime Minister","Deputy Prime Minister","2014-07-02","Business: Newark","1","House of Commons","To ask the Deputy Prime Minister, what support the Government is giving to business growth opportunities in Newark.","false","Biography information for Robert Jenrick","Newark","Robert Jenrick","904717"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66233","Deputy Prime Minister","false","2014-07-08","<p>I have been in regular dialogue with Leeds City Region LEP to discuss their Strategic Economic plan we have now concluded a Growth Deal with Leeds City Region.</p><p>This deal will include Â£571m from the Government's Local Growth Fund to support economic growth in the area â with Â£60m of new funding confirmed for 2015/16. This will lead to investment in local transport, housing sites and colleges.</p><p> </p>","Tunbridge Wells","Greg Clark",,"2014-07-08T15:18:26.5297031Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66233/answer","Biography information for Greg Clark","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66233/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66233/answer",,,,,"58","Deputy Prime Minister","Deputy Prime Minister","2014-07-02","Local Government: Leeds","1","House of Commons","To ask the Deputy Prime Minister, what discussions he has had with the Leeds City Region Local Enterprise Partnership on devolving powers and responsibilities from central government.","false","Biography information for Jason McCartney","Colne Valley","Jason McCartney","904719"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/64871","Attorney General","false","2014-07-07","<p>As and when matters are brought to the attention of the Serious Fraud Office (SFO) they are assessed in the context of the SFO's remit to investigate fraud, bribery and corruption. If appropriate, relevant matters will be considered for criminal investigation in line with SFO internal procedures. The SFO does not comment on its assessments or their status at any one time but does publish on its website details of those cases formally adopted for criminal investigation, whenever this is possible without prejudice to the investigation.</p><p> </p>","Beaconsfield","Mr Dominic Grieve",,"2014-07-07T15:35:30.0378534Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/64871/answer","Biography information for Mr Dominic Grieve","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/64871/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/64871/answer",,,,,"88","Attorney General","Attorney General","2014-07-01","Corruption: Tanzania","1","House of Commons","To ask the Attorney General, what reports he has received of bribery of foreign officials in Tanzania by African Barrack Gold plc; and whether the SFO plans to investigate those reports.","false","Biography information for Lisa Nandy","Wigan","Lisa Nandy","203352"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/64872","Attorney General","false","2014-07-16","<p>A table setting out the proportion of the money spent on consultancy fees by the Crown Prosecution Service (CPS) paid to companies for services in financial years from 2010/11 to 2013/14 has been placed in the Library of the House, together with the corresponding expenditure. The CPS financial reporting systems are configured to provide information based on financial rather than calendar years.</p>","Kenilworth and Southam","Jeremy Wright",,"2014-07-16T15:17:21.04",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/64872/answer","Biography information for Jeremy Wright","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/64872/answer","CPS consultancy data 2010-2014.docx","CPS consultancy data 2010-2014.docx","CPS consultancy data 2010 -2014","CPS consultancy data 2010 -2014","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/64872/answer","North East Hertfordshire","Oliver Heald","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/64872/answer/previousversion/8474","Biography information for Sir Oliver Heald","88","Attorney General","Attorney General","2014-07-01","Crown Prosecution Service","1","House of Commons","To ask the Attorney General, pursuant to the Answer of 16 June 2014, Official Report, column 389W, on the legal profession, what proportion of the money spent on consultancy fees by the Crown Prosecution Service was paid to which companies for what services in (a) 2010, (b) 2011, (c) 2012, (d) 2013 and (e) 2014 to date.","false","Biography information for Keith Vaz","Leicester East","Keith Vaz","203402"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/64873","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2014-07-08","<p>The UK recognises the value of learning from others by keeping abreast of developments in Europe and internationally. However, we believe that this can be achieved through less bureaucratic routes than a European Alliance for Apprenticeships. In England, we do not propose to participate but the devolved administrations are free to do so if they believe that the Alliance is the appropriate framework for sharing best practice.</p><p>We are already taking strong action to improve opportunities for young people by funding record numbers of apprenticeships, new traineeships and improved maths and English training. These actions, along with the record number of jobs, have contributed to the 32.8% fall in youth unemployment over the past year.</p>","West Suffolk","Matthew Hancock",,"2014-07-08T15:51:35.2293028Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/64873/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/64873/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/64873/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2014-07-01","Apprentices","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, what steps his Department has taken to create synergies with the European Alliance for Apprenticeships in improving work opportunities for young people.","false","Biography information for Nigel Dodds","Belfast North","Mr Nigel Dodds","203397"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/64874","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2014-07-08","<p>Local Enterprise Partnerships (LEPs) have been established as voluntary partnerships of local business and public sector leaders, and board membership is a matter for LEPs themselves. This information will not be collected centrally.</p>","Sevenoaks","Michael Fallon",,"2014-07-08T15:49:35.3961434Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/64874/answer","Biography information for Sir Michael Fallon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/64874/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/64874/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2014-07-01","Local Enterprise Partnerships","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, pursuant to the Answer of 16 June 2014, Official Report, column 423W, on local enterprise partnerships, if he will make it his policy that his Department should record the gender composition of local enterprise partnerships boards for the purpose of strengthening equality impact assessments.","false","Biography information for Tom Blenkinsop","Middlesbrough South and East Cleveland","Tom Blenkinsop","203386"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/64875","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2014-07-08","<p>The duty holder works in consultation with specialist contractors who are qualified to carry out any necessary maintenance relating to asbestos.</p><p>Under the Control of Asbestos Regulations 2012, there is a requirement for a competence to undertake this function. As this is very specific legislation, competence would require knowledge, experience and a suitable qualification (BOHS P405) or a combination of two or more of these requirements.</p><p>A role-specific bespoke course may be arranged to meet the client's needs provided by a competent body.</p>","East Dunbartonshire","Jo Swinson",,"2014-07-08T15:38:32.5692626Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/64875/answer","Biography information for Jo Swinson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/64875/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/64875/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2014-07-01","Asbestos","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, pursuant to the Answer of 30 June 2014, Official Report, column 461W, on asbestos, what training does the responsible person as a duty holder in line with Health and Safety Executive guidance receive in order to perform their duties.","false","Biography information for Katy Clark","North Ayrshire and Arran","Katy Clark","203387"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/64876","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2014-07-07","<p> </p><p>The Insolvency Service's Redundancy Payments Service has paid out a total of Â£59,207,942.40 to the former employees of Woolworths, and of this, Â£18,188,224.54 was paid in respect of protective awards.</p><p> </p>","East Dunbartonshire","Jo Swinson",,"2014-07-07T13:51:18.9258728Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/64876/answer","Biography information for Jo Swinson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/64876/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/64876/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2014-07-01","Woolworths","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, pursuant to the Answer of 30 June 2014, Official Report, columns 464W, on insolvency, how much the Insolvency Service's Redundancy Payments Service paid in relation to the collapse of Woolworths; and how much of that amount was paid in respect of protective awards.","false","Biography information for Diana Johnson","Kingston upon Hull North","Diana Johnson","203335"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/64877","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2014-07-07","<p> </p><p>Higher Education Institutions have had specific duties to provide reasonable adjustments under the Equality Act since 2010.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The Department for Business, Innovation and Skills is in regular contact with representatives of Higher Education Institutions as part of the preparation of the new guidance on Disabled Students Allowances, which will be available in the autumn.</p><p> </p>","Havant","Mr David Willetts",,"2014-07-07T14:02:14.07329Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/64877/answer","Biography information for Lord Willetts","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/64877/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/64877/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2014-07-01","Disabled Students' Allowances","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, with reference to the statement of 7 April 2014, Official Report, columns 1-2WS, on higher education (student support), what new requirements will be put on higher education institutions; and what steps he is taking to ensure those institutions are prepared to fulfil these requirements.","false","Biography information for Tracey Crouch","Chatham and Aylesford","Tracey Crouch","203353"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/64878","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2014-07-08","<p> </p><p>Details of the number of complaints that Trading Standards have received relating to the sale of sick puppies would rest with each local authority and are not held centrally.</p><p> </p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice",,"2014-07-08T10:12:38.6031588Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/64878/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/64878/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/64878/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2014-07-01","Pets: Sales","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, how many complaints Trading Standards have received relating to the sale of unwell puppies in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Andrew Stephenson","Pendle","Andrew Stephenson","203196"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/64879","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2014-07-08","<p>The Government's careers inspiration policy encourages employers and schools to work together to enthuse young people about career options to help them develop the skills and attitude needed. The National Careers Service helps to bring IT sector employers and schools together.</p><p>The National Curriculum for both primary and secondary schools from September 2014 will include a new compulsory computing element including a greater emphasis on the principles of computational thinking and practical programming skills.</p><p>Leading employers including IBM and the Test Factory are working together to design new apprenticeship standards as part of our Trailblazer programme.</p>","West Suffolk","Matthew Hancock",,"2014-07-08T16:04:23.413689Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/64879/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/64879/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/64879/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2014-07-01","Vocational Guidance: ICT","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, what steps he is taking to promote careers in the IT sector to young people.","false","Biography information for Jim Shannon","Strangford","Jim Shannon","203218"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/64880","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2014-07-08","<p>6 people working in the Sheffield headquarters of the British Business Bank have been recruited since December 2013.</p>","West Suffolk","Matthew Hancock",,"2014-07-08T16:01:53.5976832Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/64880/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/64880/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/64880/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2014-07-01","British Business Bank","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, pursuant to the Answer of 30 June 2014, Official Report, column 461W, on the British Business Bank, how many of the 44 people working in the Sheffield headquarters of the British Business Bank have been recruited since December 2013.","false","Biography information for Paul Blomfield","Sheffield Central","Paul Blomfield","203232"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/64881","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2014-07-08","<p>I will be looking at the employment tribunal ruling in the Comet case, and its consequences, carefully. As the appeal period has yet to elapse, it would be inappropriate for me to comment further at this stage.</p>","East Dunbartonshire","Jo Swinson",,"2014-07-08T15:35:41.4077908Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/64881/answer","Biography information for Jo Swinson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/64881/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/64881/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2014-07-01","Redundancy","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, in light of the collapse of Comet and the recent industrial tribunal ruling on employee compensation, what plans he has to issue guidance on the law relating to the role of administrators in consulting employees regarding redundancy.","false","Biography information for Alan Johnson","Kingston upon Hull West and Hessle","Alan Johnson","203234"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/64882","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2014-07-08","<p>The data requested are not available in the Insolvency Service's data warehouse in a form that would allow this question to be answered. The data for individual bankrupts are held on the Insolvency Service's case management system, but cannot be extracted and aggregated except at disproportionate cost.</p>","East Dunbartonshire","Jo Swinson",,"2014-07-08T15:43:34.4262878Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/64882/answer","Biography information for Jo Swinson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/64882/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/64882/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2014-07-01","Bankruptcy","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, what the (a) average total debt, secured and unsecured, in debtor petition bankruptcies, (b)  average total debt, secured and unsecured, in creditor petition bankruptcies and (c) median unsecured debt in all bankruptcies was of individuals who filed for bankruptcy in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Stella Creasy","Walthamstow","Stella Creasy","203245"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/64883","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2014-07-08","<p>The average debt level of an individual that was granted a Debt Relief Order in England and Wales in each of the last five years can be found in table 1 below.</p><p><strong><em>Table 1: Average Liabilities of Individuals granted a Debt Relief Order<sup>1</sup></em></strong></p><table><tbody><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p>Average Liability (Â£)</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2009/10</p></td><td><p>8,717</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2010/11</p></td><td><p>8,453</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2011/12</p></td><td><p>8,504</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2012/13</p></td><td><p>8,410</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2013/14</p></td><td><p>8,554</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p><strong><sup>1</sup></strong><strong>Including those under enquiry or revoked at a later date</strong></p>","East Dunbartonshire","Jo Swinson",,"2014-07-08T15:41:23.8132937Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/64883/answer","Biography information for Jo Swinson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/64883/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/64883/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2014-07-01","Debts","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, what the average total debt was of individuals who filed for a debt relief order in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Stella Creasy","Walthamstow","Stella Creasy","203246"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/64884","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2014-07-08","<p>I refer my Hon. Friend to the answer given by my Rt. Hon. Friend the Minister for the Cabinet Office (Francis Maude) on Monday 7 July 2014, Official Report, column reference 5-6W.</p>","East Dunbartonshire","Jo Swinson","203297","2014-07-08T15:46:48.8354801Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/64884/answer","Biography information for Jo Swinson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/64884/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/64884/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2014-07-01","Members: Correspondence","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, what steps his Department is taking to increase the number of ministerial replies sent to hon. Members in electronic form only.","false","Biography information for Simon Kirby","Brighton, Kemptown","Simon Kirby","203286"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/64885","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2014-07-08","<p>The Higher Education-Business and Community Interaction survey showed that contract research from business carried out by Higher Education Institutions (HEIs) amounted to Â£441m in 12-13. However, information is not held on the precise terms of these contracts or the physical locations in which they are fulfilled.</p><p>Where an HEI is in receipt of research grants from the science budget and HE funding bodies, a requirement of the funding is that the outcomes are made publicly available, although HEIs are also encouraged to secure necessary intellectual property protection to enable subsequent exploitation. The Government is also implementing a policy of âOpen Accessâ to the published findings of this publicly funded research. In the case of research consultancy, where the research is entirely funded by business, then the outcome would normally be owned by the business.</p><p>Government is committed to ensure the application of research and getting universities and business working more closely together. World Economic Forum evaluation now ranks UK among the top 5 in the world for university-industry collaboration in R&amp;D. Individual institutions have obligations under State Aid regulations and under their Charity status to ensure that their contract work with business is managed appropriately.</p>","Havant","Mr David Willetts",,"2014-07-08T16:07:18.8102067Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/64885/answer","Biography information for Lord Willetts","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/64885/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/64885/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2014-07-01","Higher Education: Research","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, what proportion of research and development contracts undertaken by publicly-funded universities for private companies are covered by clauses that prohibit the publication of the research and development results on grounds of commercial confidentiality; and what proportion of such contracts are undertaken in facilities paid for by the public purse.","false","Biography information for Paul Flynn","Newport West","Paul Flynn","203269"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/64886","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2014-07-08","<p>Inspections for asbestos containing materials are carried out in buildings owned or managed by Department for Business, Innovation and Skills in accordance with statutory requirements.</p><p>The asbestos regulations require all buildings containing asbestos to be inspected a minimum of once every twelve months. The level and type of asbestos in each building would dictate any additional inspections, maintenance and remedial work to be carried out in a particular building.</p><p> </p><p>The management plan, including records and drawings, should be reviewed every 12 months and any identified or suspected ACM must be inspected and its condition assessed periodically, to check that it has not deteriorated or been damaged.</p>","East Dunbartonshire","Jo Swinson",,"2014-07-08T16:09:59.8434567Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/64886/answer","Biography information for Jo Swinson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/64886/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/64886/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2014-07-01","Asbestos","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, pursuant to the Answer of 30 June 2014, Official Report, column 461W, on asbestos, how often inspections for asbestos containing materials are carried out in buildings owned or managed by his Department.","false","Biography information for Katy Clark","North Ayrshire and Arran","Katy Clark","203337"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/64887","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2014-07-08","<p>I refer my Hon. Friend to the answer given by my Rt. Hon. Friend the Minister for the Cabinet Office (Francis Maude) on Monday 7 July 2014, Official Report, column reference 5-6W.</p>","East Dunbartonshire","Jo Swinson","203286","2014-07-08T15:46:48.9187162Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/64887/answer","Biography information for Jo Swinson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/64887/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/64887/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2014-07-01","Members: Correspondence","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, if he will estimate the total number of ministerial replies from his Department to hon. Members in a parliamentary session; and what proportion of such replies are sent (a) by letter and (b) by email.","false","Biography information for Simon Kirby","Brighton, Kemptown","Simon Kirby","203297"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/64888","Cabinet Office","false","2014-07-07","<p>I refer the hon. Member to my Written Statement of 13 May 2014: Column 17WS.Information on the number of responses sent via email or letter is not held.</p><p>The Cabinet Office encourages all Departments to communicate with hon. Members via electronic mail where appropriate. Guidance on handling correspondence from Members of Parliament, Peers, MEPs and members of devolved administrations will be updated in due course.</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/61196/guide-handling-gov-correspondence.pdf" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/61196/guide-handling-gov-correspondence.pdf</a></p><p> </p>","Horsham","Mr Francis Maude","203298","2014-07-07T15:26:24.6738934Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/64888/answer","Biography information for Lord Maude of Horsham","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/64888/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/64888/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2014-07-01","Members: Correspondence","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, what steps his Department is taking to increase the number of ministerial replies sent to hon. Members in electronic form only.","false","Biography information for Simon Kirby","Brighton, Kemptown","Simon Kirby","203285"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/64889","Cabinet Office","false","2014-07-07","<p>Details of the national security vetting policy and process are set out in the document HMG Personnel Security Controls (available from the House of Commons Library or online at <a href="http://www.gov.uk/government/publications/hmg-personnel-security-controls" target="_blank">www.gov.uk/government/publications/hmg-personnel-security-controls</a>). It has been the policy of successive governments not to comment on staff subject to national security vetting.</p><p> </p>","Horsham","Mr Francis Maude",,"2014-07-07T15:31:57.3737661Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/64889/answer","Biography information for Lord Maude of Horsham","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/64889/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/64889/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2014-07-01","Civil Servants: Vetting","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, what the difference is between standard security checks and developed vetting carried out in respect of officials employed in the Civil Service; how many officials in No. 10 Downing Street have been subject to (a) standard security clearance and (b) developed vetting; and what limitations are placed on officials in No. 10 Downing Street who have not undergone developed vetting.","false","Biography information for Steve McCabe","Birmingham, Selly Oak","Steve McCabe","203199"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/64890","Cabinet Office","false","2014-07-08","<p>Assessments are ongoing and commercially sensitive.</p><p> </p>","Horsham","Mr Francis Maude",,"2014-07-08T16:14:26.5588118Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/64890/answer","Biography information for Lord Maude of Horsham","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/64890/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/64890/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2014-07-01","Shared Services Connected","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, if he will publish the impact assessment for the Shared Services Connected Limited venture.","false","Biography information for Paul Blomfield","Sheffield Central","Paul Blomfield","203200"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/64892","Cabinet Office","false","2014-07-07","<p>I refer the hon. Member to my Written Statement of 13 May 2014: Column 17WS.Information on the number of responses sent via email or letter is not held.</p><p>The Cabinet Office encourages all Departments to communicate with hon. Members via electronic mail where appropriate. Guidance on handling correspondence from Members of Parliament, Peers, MEPs and members of devolved administrations will be updated in due course.</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/61196/guide-handling-gov-correspondence.pdf" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/61196/guide-handling-gov-correspondence.pdf</a></p><p> </p>","Horsham","Mr Francis Maude","203285","2014-07-07T15:26:24.7676416Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/64892/answer","Biography information for Lord Maude of Horsham","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/64892/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/64892/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2014-07-01","Members: Correspondence","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, if he will estimate the total number of ministerial replies from his Department to hon. Members in a parliamentary session; and what proportion of such replies are sent (a) by letter and (b) by email.","false","Biography information for Simon Kirby","Brighton, Kemptown","Simon Kirby","203298"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/64893","Cabinet Office","false","2014-07-07","<p>The information requested falls within the responsibility of the UK Statistics Authority. I have asked the Authority to reply.</p><p> </p>","Ruislip, Northwood and Pinner","Mr Nick Hurd",,"2014-07-07T10:03:03.38",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/64893/answer","Biography information for Mr Nick Hurd","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/64893/answer","PQs 203349 and 203496.pdf ; PQ289 & 290.xlsx","PQs 203349 and 203496.pdf ; PQ289 & 290.xlsx","ONS Letter to Member ; Letter attachment - Employment","ONS Letter to Member ; Letter attachment - Employment","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/64893/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2014-07-01","Older Workers","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, how many people over 50 years old are employed in each region and constituent part of the UK; and what proportion of people aged over 50 years old living in the region and constituent part do they represent in each such case.","false","Biography information for Stephen Timms","East Ham","Stephen Timms","203349"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/64894","HM Treasury","false","2014-07-08","<p>HM Revenue &amp; Customs (HMRC) deploys its resources according to risk and has a continuous programme of work assuring tax compliance across a range of taxes, including VAT, in the public (and private) sector. Since 2008 there has been a dedicated operational unit responsible for compliance activity in the public sector, and they aim to treat the public sector in the same way as HMRC treats similar customers in the private sector.</p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke",,"2014-07-08T14:28:19.8642088Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/64894/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/64894/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/64894/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2014-07-01","Public Sector: VAT","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what steps HM Revenue and Customs is taking to ensure that public sector bodies do not underpay VAT.","false","Biography information for Tom Blenkinsop","Middlesbrough South and East Cleveland","Tom Blenkinsop","203224"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/64895","HM Treasury","false","2014-07-09","<p>Parents' payments from their Tax-Free Childcare accounts will only go to registered childcare providers. HMRC will investigate in the exceptional circumstances where it suspects the payments were not used for childcare. The Childcare Payments Bill sets out HMRC's proposed compliance powers.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The administration costs of the scheme will be settled once the scheme's design has been finalised.</p>","Loughborough","Nicky Morgan",,"2014-07-09T16:01:31.5417907Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/64895/answer","Biography information for Nicky Morgan","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/64895/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/64895/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2014-07-01","Children: Day Care","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what steps he plans to take to ensure that parents use their tax-free childcare accounts to pay for childcare; and what additional costs such checks will place on HM Revenue and Customs.","false","Biography information for Lucy Powell","Manchester Central","Lucy Powell","203316"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/64896","HM Treasury","true","2014-07-07","<p>The following table is based on finalised tax credits administrative data for each financial year. The latest data available are 2012-13.</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td rowspan="2"><p>Tax Year</p></td><td> </td><td colspan="3"><p>Average tax credit award for households who are classified as 'in work'</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Average tax credit award for households who are classified as 'out of work'</p></td><td><p>Households who are classified as self employed only</p></td><td><p>Households who are classified as employed only</p></td><td><p>Households who are classified as both employed and self employed</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2007-08</p></td><td><p>Â£4,300</p></td><td><p>Â£5,800</p></td><td><p>Â£2,800</p></td><td><p>Â£3,300</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2008-09</p></td><td><p>Â£4,700</p></td><td><p>Â£6,500</p></td><td><p>Â£3,300</p></td><td><p>Â£3,700</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2009-10</p></td><td><p>Â£5,000</p></td><td><p>Â£6,800</p></td><td><p>Â£3,700</p></td><td><p>Â£4,000</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2010-11</p></td><td><p>Â£5,200</p></td><td><p>Â£6,900</p></td><td><p>Â£3,900</p></td><td><p>Â£4,100</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2011-12</p></td><td><p>Â£5,600</p></td><td><p>Â£7,200</p></td><td><p>Â£4,500</p></td><td><p>Â£4,800</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2012-13</p></td><td><p>Â£6,000</p></td><td><p><del class="ministerial">Â£7,600</del> <ins class="ministerial">Â£<ins>7,500</ins></ins></p></td><td><p><del class="ministerial">Â£6,300</del> <ins class="ministerial">Â£<ins>6,200</ins></ins></p></td><td><p><del class="ministerial">Â£6,400</del> <ins class="ministerial">Â£<ins>6,000</ins></ins></p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p>These figures have been rounded to the nearest Â£100.</p><p> </p><p>Data from earlier years is only available at disproportionate cost.</p><p> </p><p>The increase in average tax credit awards in 2012-13 can largely be explained by the removal of the âSecond Income Thresholdâ in April 2012. This policy removed a number of higher income households from the tax credit population. As higher income households generally have lower tax credit awards, the effect of removing these households increases the average award.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","Loughborough","Nicky Morgan",,"2014-07-07T14:06:19.897Z","2015-03-24T11:54:34.01Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/64896/answer","Biography information for Nicky Morgan","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/64896/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/64896/answer","Loughborough","Nicky Morgan","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/64896/answer/previousversion/8139","Biography information for Nicky Morgan","14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2014-07-01","Welfare Tax Credits","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what average value of tax credits were paid to claimants who were (a) out of work, (b) self-employed and (c) employed in each of the last 10 years.","false","Biography information for Rachel Reeves","Leeds West","Rachel Reeves","203325"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/64897","HM Treasury","false","2014-07-07","<p>The following table is based on finalised tax credits administrative data for each financial year. The latest data available are 2012-13.</p><p> </p><p>Warrington Unitary Authority</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td> </td><td colspan="2"><p><em>Thousands</em></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Tax Year</p></td><td colspan="2"><p>Number of families in receipt of tax credits containing at least one member identified as self-employed</p></td></tr><tr><td> </td><td><p>Families benefitting from both WTC and CTC</p></td><td><p>Families benefitting from WTC Only</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2008-09</p></td><td><p>1.2</p></td><td><p>0.2</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2009-10</p></td><td><p>1.1</p></td><td><p>0.3</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2010-11</p></td><td><p>1.1</p></td><td><p>0.3</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2011-12</p></td><td><p>0.8</p></td><td><p>0.4</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2012-13</p></td><td><p>1.5</p></td><td><p>0.4</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>Warrington North Parliamentary Constituency</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td> </td><td colspan="2"><p><em>Thousands</em></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Tax Year</p></td><td colspan="2"><p>Number of families in receipt of tax credits containing at least one member identified as self-employed</p></td></tr><tr><td> </td><td><p>Families benefitting from both WTC and CTC</p></td><td><p>Families benefitting from WTC Only</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2008-09</p></td><td><p>0.5</p></td><td><p>0.1</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2009-10</p></td><td><p>0.5</p></td><td><p>0.2</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2010-11</p></td><td><p>0.5</p></td><td><p>0.2</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2011-12</p></td><td><p>0.4</p></td><td><p>0.2</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2012-13</p></td><td><p>0.7</p></td><td><p>0.2</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p> </p><p>In general, there is and has been a long term trend of growth in the number of self employed people.</p>","Loughborough","Nicky Morgan","201711","2014-07-07T15:24:16.9544837Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/64897/answer","Biography information for Nicky Morgan","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/64897/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/64897/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2014-07-01","Working Tax Credit: Self-employed","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, how many people in Warrington North constituency were self-employed and in receipt of working tax credit in each year since 2010-11.","false","Biography information for Helen Jones","Warrington North","Helen Jones","203276"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/64898","HM Treasury","false","2014-07-07","<p>Information on the amount of Official Development Assistance spent by each Government department since 2009-10 is available publicly at: https://www.gov.uk/government/organisations/department-for-international-development/about/statistics.</p>","Inverness, Nairn, Badenoch and Strathspey","Danny Alexander",,"2014-07-07T15:16:37.1918523Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/64898/answer","Biography information for Danny Alexander","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/64898/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/64898/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2014-07-01","Development Aid","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, how much Official Development Assistance was spent by each Government department in 2009-10 and in each year since (a) in cash terms, (b) at current prices and (c) as a proportion of Gross National Income.","false","Biography information for Sir Hugh Bayley","York Central","Hugh Bayley","203236"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/64899","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2014-07-07","<p> </p><p>Ministers within the Department for Communities and Local Government regularly meet colleagues from other Departments to discuss a range of matters.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The Government produced an Impact Assessment and New Burdens Assessment which were published alongside the Care Act 2014.</p><p> </p><p>We have worked collaboratively with a wide range of external partners, including representatives of local authorities, including the Local Government Association and the Association of Directors of Adult Social Services on the development of the Act and the accompanying draft regulations and guidance.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p><strong> </strong></p><p> </p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis",,"2014-07-07T15:12:50.4823586Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/64899/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/64899/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/64899/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2014-07-01","Care Act 2014","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what discussions he has had with the Secretary of State for Health on the potential effect of the Care Act 2014 on local authorities; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Andy McDonald","Middlesbrough","Andy McDonald","203281"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/64900","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2014-07-07","<p> </p><p>We will consult in due course.</p><p> </p>","Grantham and Stamford","Nick Boles",,"2014-07-07T16:23:06.7166034Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/64900/answer","Biography information for Nick Boles","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/64900/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/64900/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2014-07-01","Betting Shops: Planning Permission","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, when he expects his Department to publish a consultation document on withdrawing permitted development rights for bookmakers; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Mr Stewart Jackson","Peterborough","Mr Stewart Jackson","203326"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/64901","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2014-07-08","<p> </p><p>I refer my hon. Friend to the answer given my rt. hon. Friend, the Minister for the Cabinet Office, Paymaster General (Francis Maude) on 7 July, <em>Official Report, </em>Column 5-6W.</p><p> </p><p><strong> </strong></p><p> </p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis","203523","2014-07-08T14:22:50.6016345Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/64901/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/64901/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/64901/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2014-07-01","Members: Correspondence","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, if he will estimate the total number of ministerial replies from his Department to hon. Members in a parliamentary session; and what proportion of such replies are sent (a) by letter and (b) by email.","false","Biography information for Simon Kirby","Brighton, Kemptown","Simon Kirby","203299"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/64902","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2014-07-07","<p> </p><p>This Government is committed to supporting people's aspirations to own their own home. The number of families buying a home with the support of the Help to Buy: Equity Loan scheme, as of 31 May in the Ribble Valley Borough Council is 21; in Lancashire it is 512; and across England it is 22,831. The Department's official statistics on sales, broken down by local authority and postcode sector for England is available at: <a href="http://www.gov.uk/government/statistical-data-sets/help-to-buy-equity-loan-scheme-monthly-statistics" target="_blank">www.gov.uk/government/statistical-data-sets/help-to-buy-equity-loan-scheme-monthly-statistics</a></p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The Department does not hold information on schemes operated by the other devolved administrations.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The Help to Buy: Mortgage Guarantee scheme is managed by HM Treasury and the data is available at: <a href="http://www.gov.uk/government/publications/help-to-buy-mortgage-guarantee-scheme-quarterly-statistics-october-2013-to-march-2014" target="_blank">www.gov.uk/government/publications/help-to-buy-mortgage-guarantee-scheme-quarterly-statistics-october-2013-to-march-2014</a></p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p><strong> </strong></p><p> </p>","Keighley","Kris Hopkins",,"2014-07-07T15:08:46.0887038Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/64902/answer","Biography information for Kris Hopkins","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/64902/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/64902/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2014-07-01","Help to Buy Scheme","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, how many house purchases have been funded through the Help to Buy scheme in (a) Ribble Valley, (b) Lancashire and (c) the UK.","false","Biography information for Mr Nigel Evans","Ribble Valley","Mr Nigel Evans","203332"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/64903","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2014-07-08","<p> </p><p>When appeal 2193211 was first received by the Planning Inspectorate in February 2013, the agent, acting for the appellant, indicated in the appeal form the hearing method as the preferred choice of procedure. They felt this was appropriate as consideration should be given to complex matters requiring technical expert evidence. The Planning Inspectorate wrote to the local planning authority who indicated they felt written representations would suffice.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>After considering the information provided and applying the published criteria for determining the procedure the Planning Inspectorate applied Section 319a of the Town and Country Planning Act 1990 (as amended) and determined the written representations method was proportionate in the circumstances. No further correspondence regarding the choice of procedure was received and the appeal proceeded according to the timetable set out in the start letter which also explained the choice of procedure. The agent and the local planning authority submitted, as part of the appeal evidence, a statement of common ground which included agreement that the relevant requirements of paragraph 55 of the National Planning Policy Framework were satisfied.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p>Upon receipt of the decision, dated 29 August 2013, the appellant lodged an appeal with the High Court as he felt the requirements of paragraph 55 of the National Planning Policy Framework were satisfied, whereas the Inspector had found they were not, and that this information could have been examined verbally had the procedure been a Hearing.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>To allow for procedural fairness, it was agreed by the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government that the appeal would be re-determined by a different Inspector and would follow a Hearing or Public Inquiry once representations and considerations had been sought from the principal parties. A date for the Hearing event has been fixed for 23 July 2014.</p><p> </p><p><strong> </strong></p><p> </p>","Grantham and Stamford","Nick Boles",,"2014-07-08T16:10:34.9524877Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/64903/answer","Biography information for Nick Boles","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/64903/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/64903/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2014-07-01","Planning Permission: Gateshead","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, for what reasons he reversed the appeal decision in Gateshead Borough, ref 2193211.","false","Biography information for Mr David Anderson","Blaydon","Mr David Anderson","203360"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/64904","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2014-07-09","<p> </p><p>My Department's Integration Team has not had any contact with the European Parliament Working Group on Freedom of Religion or Belief, although we recognise the important role of the Group in raising awareness about the issue. My noble Friend, (the rt. hon. Baroness Warsi), the Senior Minister for Faith and Communities, who is also a Minister at the Foreign and Commonwealth Office, has made Freedom of Religion or Belief a priority and the government works in multilateral fora to ensure that it is afforded the international legal protection that it deserves. My noble Friend has also convened meetings of international leaders to generate practical steps to promote freedom of religion or belief and to fight religious intolerance within our societies. In the UK she chairs a Sub Group on Freedom of Religion or Belief, made up of human rights advocates, academics and civil society leaders, ensuring that government takes a well informed and inclusive approach to promoting and protecting this human right.</p><p> </p>","Bristol West","Stephen Williams",,"2014-07-09T16:31:03.9992416Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/64904/answer","Biography information for Stephen Williams","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/64904/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/64904/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2014-07-01","Religious Freedom","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what contact his officials have had with the European Parliament Working Group on Freedom of Religion or Belief in the last 12 months.","false","Biography information for Nigel Dodds","Belfast North","Mr Nigel Dodds","203396"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/64905","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2014-07-08","<p> </p><p>Challenges to planning appeal decisions are made under Section 288 of the Town and Country Planning Act 1990.</p><p> </p><p>If a challenge is successful the High Court will normally return the case to the Planning Inspectorate for it to be decided again. This does not necessarily mean that the original decision will be changed or reversed.</p><p> </p>","Grantham and Stamford","Nick Boles",,"2014-07-08T14:20:50.7070705Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/64905/answer","Biography information for Nick Boles","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/64905/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/64905/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2014-07-01","Planning Permission","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, by what process planning decisions can be reversed at the discretion of a court.","false","Biography information for Mr David Anderson","Blaydon","Mr David Anderson","203429"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/64906","Department for Culture Media and Sport","false","2014-07-08","<p>DCMS plays no role in setting the protocols that determine when, where or which flags are flown in the United Kingdom. The Department for Communities and Local Government undertook a numbers of measures to deregulate flag flying in England in 2012. The flag flying policy in Wales, Scotland and Northern Ireland is a matter for the specific devolved administrations themselves.</p>","Wantage","Mr Edward Vaizey",,"2014-07-08T09:31:13.881554Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/64906/answer","Biography information for Mr Edward Vaizey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/64906/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/64906/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2014-07-01","Flags","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, what steps he is taking to reduce bureaucratic obstacles to the flying of flags in the UK.","false","Biography information for Andrew Rosindell","Romford","Andrew Rosindell","203415"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/64907","Department for Culture Media and Sport","false","2014-07-08","<p>In the last Parliamentary session (2013-14) the number of replies to members of parliament stood at 5,860. As a rule the Department sends all responses by e-mail unless specifically requested otherwise by the Member of Parliament. We do not keep separate records of how many were sent by post compared to e-mail.</p>","Maidstone and The Weald","Mrs Helen Grant",,"2014-07-08T09:31:54.0166448Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/64907/answer","Biography information for Mrs Helen Grant","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/64907/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/64907/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2014-07-01","Members: Correspondence","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, if he will estimate the total number of ministerial replies from his Department to hon. Members in a parliamentary session; and what proportion of such replies are sent (a) by letter and (b) by email.","false","Biography information for Simon Kirby","Brighton, Kemptown","Simon Kirby","203300"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/64909","Department for Culture Media and Sport","false","2014-07-08","<p>The provider must send you an alert when you reach 80% and then 100% of the agreed data roaming limit. Operators must stop charging for data at the 100% point, unless you agree to continue to use data.</p><p> </p><p>Ofcom provides advice on using telephones abroad, including in countries outside the European Union. See:</p><p><a href="http://consumers.ofcom.org.uk/2013/03/check-your-phone-before-you-roam/" target="_blank">http://consumers.ofcom.org.uk/2013/03/check-your-phone-before-you-roam/</a> and</p><p><a href="http://consumers.ofcom.org.uk/2013/07/using-your-smartphone-or-tablet-abroad/" target="_blank">http://consumers.ofcom.org.uk/2013/07/using-your-smartphone-or-tablet-abroad/</a></p><p> </p><p>This includes the advice to talk to your UK provider before you travel - it may offer special packages for your destination.</p><p> </p>","Wantage","Mr Edward Vaizey",,"2014-07-08T09:30:31.8772221Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/64909/answer","Biography information for Mr Edward Vaizey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/64909/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/64909/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2014-07-01","Mobile Phones","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, whether he plans to introduce proposals for regulations or guidance to reduce the cost of the use of British mobile telephones roaming outside of the EU.","false","Biography information for Tom Blenkinsop","Middlesbrough South and East Cleveland","Tom Blenkinsop","203267"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/64910","Ministry of Defence","false","2014-07-07","<p>It is intended that Statistical Bulletin 6.02 will be published at 09.30am on Thursday 24 July 2014, as announced on the Ministry of Defence timetable for future releases on the GOV.UK website.</p>","South West Wiltshire","Dr Andrew Murrison",,"2014-07-07T15:42:33.5164096Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/64910/answer","Biography information for Dr Andrew Murrison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/64910/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/64910/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2014-07-01","Armed Forces: Housing","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, whether the Statistical Bulletin 6.02 on Accommodation will be published by the end of July 2014.","false","Biography information for Alison Seabeck","Plymouth, Moor View","Alison Seabeck","203274"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/64911","Ministry of Defence","false","2014-07-07","<p>There will be a formal opportunity to receive and hear the views of local residents in regard to the Marchwood proposal via the statutory planning process. Additionally in recognition of the ongoing concerns that local residents will understandably have, Ministry of Defence officials will continue to engage with local representatives and through the Local Planning Authority until the commercial arrangements are completed.<br><br>It is not yet known how interested parties will seek to develop the Marchwood site for commercial use over and above the continuing military use at this early stage in the process. Consequently, any consultation with the local community would, at this stage, be speculative. <br><br>I would expect the successful partner to consult with the local community regarding its plans for the site following the grant of the concession.</p>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne",,"2014-07-07T16:23:28.6515416Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/64911/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/64911/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/64911/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2014-07-01","Marchwood Military Port","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, if he will make it his policy formally to consult the residents of Marchwood, Hampshire, about the sale of the lease of land and facilities at the site of the military port; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Dr Julian Lewis","New Forest East","Dr Julian Lewis","203317"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/64912","Ministry of Defence","false","2014-07-08","<p>I refer the hon. Member to the answer my right hon. Friend the Minister for the Cabinet Office (Francis Maude) gave on 7 July 2014 (Official Report, columns 5-6W)</p>","Broxtowe","Anna Soubry","203525","2014-07-08T16:26:32.4360969Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/64912/answer","Biography information for Anna Soubry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/64912/answer","20140707 Hansard extract Members Correspondence.doc","20140707 Hansard extract Members Correspondence.doc","20140707 Hansard extract Members Correspondence","20140707 Hansard extract Members Correspondence","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/64912/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2014-07-01","Members: Correspondence","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, if he will estimate the total number of ministerial replies from his Department to hon. Members in a parliamentary session; and what proportion of such replies are sent (a) by letter and (b) by email.","false","Biography information for Simon Kirby","Brighton, Kemptown","Simon Kirby","203301"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/64913","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2014-07-07","<p>The Battle of the Marne is not part of the UK National Programme for the First World War Centenary commemorations. We are in regular contact with the French Government regarding Centenary commemorations, and will be guided by their plans to commemorate the Battle of the Marne, supporting them as appropriate.</p>","Boston and Skegness","Mark Simmonds",,"2014-07-07T14:16:54.069679Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/64913/answer","Biography information for Mark Simmonds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/64913/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/64913/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2014-07-01","World War I: Anniversaries","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what plans his Department has to commemorate the 100th anniversary of the First Battle of the Marne between 5 and 12 September 2014.","false","Biography information for Mr Nigel Evans","Ribble Valley","Mr Nigel Evans","203331"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/64914","Ministry of Defence","false","2014-07-09","<p>The information requested is not held by the Ministry of Defence. However NATO has agreed to consider for public release all reports from the International Board of Auditors for NATO (IBAN) from financial year 2013 onwards. Given the importance of full transparency and public accountability, we continue to call for all reports to be published except where this would prejudice Alliance security.<br><br><br>The UK remains committed to improving NATO's transparency, accountability and Value for Money to tax payers and will therefore continue to work closely with Allies and NATO on this issue.</p>","South West Wiltshire","Dr Andrew Murrison",,"2014-07-09T17:11:44.0856978Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/64914/answer","Biography information for Dr Andrew Murrison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/64914/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/64914/answer","South West Wiltshire","Dr Andrew Murrison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/64914/answer/previousversion/9255","Biography information for Dr Andrew Murrison","11","Defence","Defence","2014-07-01","NATO","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, how many (a) sets of accounts will be audited and (b) value for money studies will be completed this calendar year by the International Board of Auditors of NATO; how many of these audits were completed in the first six months of the year; when NATO will publish these accounts and audit reports; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Sir Hugh Bayley","York Central","Hugh Bayley","203405"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/64915","Ministry of Defence","false","2014-07-09","<p>Having considered the objection raised I decided to proceed with the Treasury Minute on Contingent Liability as this work is an essential enabler in allowing the Ministry of Defence (MOD) to deliver its projects and estate maintenance requirements on estates where nuclear assets are sited.<br><br>It is the MOD's intent to limit the contractor's liability at Her Majesty's Naval Base Clyde to Â£100,000. Since no commercial contractor could reasonably be expected to assume total liabilities or to be able to insure against them. Such a liability can only be borne by the State.</p>","South West Wiltshire","Dr Andrew Murrison",,"2014-07-09T16:22:09.8705286Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/64915/answer","Biography information for Dr Andrew Murrison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/64915/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/64915/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2014-07-01","Clyde Naval Base","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, for what reasons the Parliamentary Under-Secretary of State and Minister for International Security Strategy approved the proposals to limit contractor liability at HMNB Clyde to Â£100,000 despite the objection by the hon. Member for Newport West.","false","Biography information for Paul Flynn","Newport West","Paul Flynn","203416"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/64916","Department for Education","false","2014-07-10","<p>As Warrington only became a local authority in 1998 as a result of local government reorganisation, comparable funding data is only available from this date.</p><p>Average per pupil revenue funding figures, from the Department to local authorities, for pupils aged 3-10 (primary) and 11-15 (secondary) for Warrington specifically for years 1997-98 to 2005-06 are as follows. These figures are in cash terms:</p><table><tbody><tr><td><p><strong>Average Per Pupil Revenue Funding </strong></p><p><strong>(cash)</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>1997-98</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>1998-99</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>1999-00</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2000-01</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2001-02</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2002-03</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2003-04</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2004-05</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2005-06</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Warrington LA (primary)</p></td><td><p>1,856</p></td><td><p>1,973</p></td><td><p>2,123</p></td><td><p>2,337</p></td><td><p>2,540</p></td><td><p>2,670</p></td><td><p>2,896</p></td><td><p>3,046</p></td><td><p>3,321</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Warrington LA (secondary)</p></td><td><p>2,579</p></td><td><p>2,711</p></td><td><p>2,841</p></td><td><p>3,075</p></td><td><p>3,287</p></td><td><p>3,472</p></td><td><p>3,633</p></td><td><p>3,886</p></td><td><p>4,124</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p>These figures are in real terms using June 2014 GDP deflators in 2013-14 prices:</p><table><tbody><tr><td><p><strong>Average Per Pupil Revenue Funding </strong></p><p><strong>(real)</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>1997- 98</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>1998-99</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>1999-00</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2000-01</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2001-02</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2002-03</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2003-04</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2004-05</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2005-06</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Warrington LA (primary)</p></td><td><p>2,618</p></td><td><p>2,730</p></td><td><p>2,881</p></td><td><p>3,149</p></td><td><p>3,333</p></td><td><p>3,424</p></td><td><p>3,642</p></td><td><p>3,728</p></td><td><p>3,992</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Warrington LA (secondary)</p></td><td><p>3,637</p></td><td><p>3,752</p></td><td><p>3,856</p></td><td><p>4,145</p></td><td><p>4,313</p></td><td><p>4,452</p></td><td><p>4,570</p></td><td><p>4,757</p></td><td><p>4,957</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p>Per pupil figures using standard spending assessment (SSA)/education formula share (EFS) allocations and pupils aged 3-15.</p><p>With the introduction of the dedicated schools grant (DSG) in 2006-07, the changes to the funding mechanism meant figures were no longer comparable with previous years.</p><p>The 1997-98 to 2005-06 figures are based on EFS which formed the education part of the local government finance settlement, plus various grants. This was an assessment of what local authorities needed to fund education rather than what they spent. The DSG is based largely on an authority's previous spending. In addition, the DSG has a different coverage to EFS. EFS comprised a schools block and a local education authority (LEA) block (to cover LEA central functions) whereas DSG only covers the EFS school block. LEA block items are still funded through DCLG's local government finance settlement but education items cannot be separately identified. Consequently, there is a break in the department's time series as the two sets of data are not comparable.</p><p>To provide a comparison for 2006-07 DSG, the Department has isolated the EFS school block equivalent funding in 2005-06; as described above this does not represent the totality of âeducation' funding in that year.</p><p>Figures for financial years 2005 to 2013 are shown below. These are in cash terms:</p><table><tbody><tr><td><p><strong>Average revenue per pupil funding (cash)</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2005-06</strong><br><strong> (baseline)</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2006-07</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2007-08</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2008-09</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2009-10</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2010-11</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2011-12</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2012-13</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Warrington LA</p></td><td><p>3,630</p></td><td><p>3,840</p></td><td><p>4,100</p></td><td><p>4,300</p></td><td><p>4,490</p></td><td><p>4,730</p></td><td><p>4,670</p></td><td><p>4,670</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p>These are in real terms using June 2014 GDP deflators in 2013-14 prices:</p><table><tbody><tr><td><p><strong>Average revenue per pupil funding (cash)</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2005-06</strong><br><strong> (baseline)</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2006-07</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2007-08</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2008-09</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2009-10</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2010-11</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2011-12</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2012-13</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Warrington LA</p></td><td><p>4,370</p></td><td><p>4,490</p></td><td><p>4,670</p></td><td><p>4,760</p></td><td><p>4,850</p></td><td><p>4,970</p></td><td><p>4,800</p></td><td><p>4,750</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p>Per pupil figures are using DSG allocations plus other schools related grants, e.g. school standards grant, school standards grant (personalisation), standards fund etc. and pupils aged 3-15 rounded to the nearest Â£10. Most of the additional grants were mainstreamed into DSG in 2011-12.</p><p>With the changes to DSG funding in financial year 2013 to 2014, i.e. funding allocated through three blocks, namely schools, early years and high needs, there is no longer a comparable overall figure with previous years. The table below shows the DSG schools block unit funding figures in cash and real terms for Warrington LA.</p><table><tbody><tr><td><p><strong>DSG schools block per pupil funding</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2013-14</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2014-15</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Warrington LA (cash)</p></td><td><p>4,219</p></td><td><p>4,219</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Warrington LA (real)*</p></td><td><p>4,219</p></td><td><p>4,128</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p>*Real terms figures shown in 2013-14 prices using GDP deflators at 27.06.14</p><p>Since 2011-12 schools have received the Pupil Premium which targets funding at pupils from the most deprived backgrounds to help them achieve their full potential. In 2011-12, the Premium was allocated for each pupil known to be eligible for Free School Meals, looked after children and children of parents in the armed services. In 2012-13 coverage was expanded to include pupils known to have been eligible for Free School Meals at any point in the last six years. The amounts per pupil amounts for each type of pupil are shown in following table in cash terms:</p><table><tbody><tr><td><p><strong>Pupil Premium per pupil (Â£)</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2011-12</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2012-13</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2013-14</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2014-15</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Free School Meal Pupil Primary</p></td><td><p>488</p></td><td><p>623</p></td><td><p>953</p></td><td><p>1,300</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Free School Meal Pupil Secondary</p></td><td><p>488</p></td><td><p>623</p></td><td><p>900</p></td><td><p>935</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Service Children</p></td><td><p>200</p></td><td><p>250</p></td><td><p>300</p></td><td><p>300</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Looked After Children</p></td><td><p>488</p></td><td><p>623</p></td><td><p>900</p></td><td><p>1,900*</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p>*Also includes children adopted from care</p><p>Total Pupil Premium allocations for Warrington local authority for each year are shown in the following table in cash terms:</p><table><tbody><tr><td><p><strong>Pupil Premium Allocations (Â£ million)</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2011-12</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2012-13</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2013-14</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2014-15</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Warrington</p></td><td><p>1.720</p></td><td><p>3.389</p></td><td><p>5.281</p></td><td><p>6.899</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p>These figures in real terms:</p><table><tbody><tr><td><p><strong>Pupil Premium Allocations (Â£ million)</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2011-12</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2012-13</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2013-14</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2014-15</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Warrington</p></td><td><p>1.769</p></td><td><p>3.447</p></td><td><p>5.281</p></td><td><p>6.750</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p>Price Base: Real terms at 2013-14 prices, based on GDP deflators as at 27.06.2014</p><p>The table below shows capital funding for the financial years that are available. The data is in cash terms as allocations are phased across more than one year making real terms calculations meaningless.Complete information on the split of capital between phases of education is not held centrally.</p><table><tbody><tr><td><p><strong>Warrington</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Capital funding</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>1998-99</p></td><td><p>3.70</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>1999-00</p></td><td><p>4.70</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2000-01</p></td><td><p>8.70</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2001-02</p></td><td><p>10.00</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2002-03</p></td><td><p>11.70</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2003-04</p></td><td><p>10.60</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2004-05</p></td><td><p>10.30</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2005-06</p></td><td><p>12.20</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2006-07</p></td><td><p>12.70</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2007-08</p></td><td><p>10.40</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2008-09</p></td><td><p>10.60</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2009-10</p></td><td><p>19.40</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2010-11</p></td><td><p>18.40</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2011-12</p></td><td><p>5.60</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2012-13</p></td><td><p>7.10</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2013-14</p></td><td><p>8.60</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p>Warrington also received Â£1.3 million in 2007-8, Â£3.4 million in 2008-9, Â£18.2 million in 2009-10, and Â£0.9 million in 2010-11 under the BSF programme.</p><p><strong>Notes:</strong></p><p>1. Capital allocations includes capital grant and supported borrowing allocations.</p><p>2. Figures are rounded to the nearest Â£100,000.</p><p><strong>Sources:</strong></p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/dedicated-schools-grant-2014-to-2015" target="_blank">www.gov.uk/government/publications/dedicated-schools-grant-2014-to-2015</a></p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/pupil-premium-2013-to-2014-final-allocation-tables" target="_blank">www.gov.uk/government/publications/pupil-premium-2013-to-2014-final-allocation-tables</a></p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/pupil-premium-2014-to-2015-illustrative-allocation-tables" target="_blank">www.gov.uk/government/publications/pupil-premium-2014-to-2015-illustrative-allocation-tables</a></p><p><a href="http://webarchive.nationalarchives.gov.uk/20131216163513/http:/www.education.gov.uk/schools/adminandfinance/financialmanagement/schoolsrevenuefunding" target="_blank">webarchive.nationalarchives.gov.uk/20131216163513/http://www.education.gov.uk/schools/adminandfinance/financialmanagement/schoolsrevenuefunding</a></p>","Yeovil","Mr David Laws",,"2014-07-10T16:20:22.2983078Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/64916/answer","Biography information for Mr David Laws","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/64916/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/64916/answer","Yeovil","Mr David Laws","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/64916/answer/previousversion/8585","Biography information for Mr David Laws","60","Education","Education","2014-07-01","Education: Warrington","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, how much (a) revenue and (b) capital funding was provided to each pupil in state (i) primary and (ii) secondary schools in Warrington in (A) cash terms and (B) at 2014 prices in each year since 1995-96.","false","Biography information for Helen Jones","Warrington North","Helen Jones","203329"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/64917","Department for Education","false","2014-07-07","<p>Information is not available in the form requested. Reports on the performance of Departments in handling correspondence from hon. Members and peers are published by the Minister for the Cabinet Office and Paymaster General each year and include numbers of letters to which Ministers reply. The report for the calendar year 2013 (Official Report 13 May 2014, 17WS) shows that 16,898 such letters were received by Department for Education Ministers. Most correspondence from hon. Members continues to be received as letters and is replied to in the same format, although Ministers will continue to reply in email form when they consider it appropriate to do so.</p>","South West Norfolk","Elizabeth Truss","203526","2014-07-07T10:12:10.2498357Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/64917/answer","Biography information for Elizabeth Truss","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/64917/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/64917/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2014-07-01","Members: Correspondence","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, if he will estimate the total number of ministerial replies from his Department to hon. Members in a parliamentary session; and what proportion of such replies are sent (a) by letter and (b) by email.","false","Biography information for Simon Kirby","Brighton, Kemptown","Simon Kirby","203302"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/64918","Department for Education","false","2014-07-14","<p>My hon. Friend the Parliamentary Under-Secretary of State for Children and Families is responsible for special educational needs and disability issues within the Department for Education. He has had numerous meetings with the parents of disabled children to discuss a wide range of issues. I have regular meetings with all of my ministerial colleagues on subjects of mutual interest.</p><p> </p><p>The guidance in the draft Special Educational Needs and Disability Code of Practice includes a separate chapter on the early years and also makes clear that local authorities must include details of childcare for disabled children in their local offer of support for children who are disabled or have special educational needs.</p>","South West Norfolk","Elizabeth Truss",,"2014-07-14T17:50:18.536372Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/64918/answer","Biography information for Elizabeth Truss","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/64918/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/64918/answer","South West Norfolk","Elizabeth Truss","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/64918/answer/previousversion/8588","Biography information for Elizabeth Truss","60","Education","Education","2014-07-01","Children: Day Care","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, how many meetings the Parliamentary Under-Secretary for Childcare and Early Years has had with parents of disabled children about improving access, affordability and quality of childcare for disabled children since he was appointed.","false","Biography information for Lucy Powell","Manchester Central","Lucy Powell","203388"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/64919","Department for Education","false","2014-07-07","<p>The information requested has been placed in the House Library.</p>","Crewe and Nantwich","Mr Edward Timpson",,"2014-07-07T15:50:35.0759799Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/64919/answer","Biography information for Edward Timpson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/64919/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/64919/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2014-07-01","Pupils: Qualifications","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, how many and what proportion of pupils who did not have a statement of special educational needs in each school achieved no qualifications by the end of key stage 4 in the most recent year for which figures are available.","false","Biography information for Andrew Griffiths","Burton","Andrew Griffiths","203334"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/64921","Department for Education","false","2014-07-07","<p>Major reforms in the Children and Families Act 2014 are helping to speed up the legal adoption process for children in England, support quicker matching and ensure earlier placement of children with foster families who may go on to adopt them. Adoption scorecards were introduced in 2012 and are driving improvements locally. We implemented a new adopter approval process last year and under this new process prospective adopters can now be approved in just six months. New training materials and other tools have been developed by the College of Social Work and Research in Practice to improve the skills of social workers so they are better placed to quickly judge what is best for each child. In 2012-13, the number of adopters was 34% up on the year before.</p>","Crewe and Nantwich","Mr Edward Timpson",,"2014-07-07T15:28:29.7732849Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/64921/answer","Biography information for Edward Timpson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/64921/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/64921/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2014-07-01","Adoption","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what steps his Department is taking to reduce the time taken to adopt a child.","false","Biography information for Jim Shannon","Strangford","Jim Shannon","203216"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/64922","Department for Education","false","2014-07-07","<p>Professor Eileen Munro undertook a wide-ranging independent review of the child protection system in England reporting in 2011. This review looked at the system as a whole, including the adequacy of the child protection legislation. The Department for Education has since clarified the legislation through the revised statutory safeguarding guidance<em>, </em>âWorking Together to Safeguard Children 2013' so all organisations working with vulnerable children know what the law says they and others must do.</p><p>The Department will continue to monitor the current legislation and review options to strengthen the system to keep children safe.</p>","Crewe and Nantwich","Mr Edward Timpson",,"2014-07-07T15:29:56.7890701Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/64922/answer","Biography information for Edward Timpson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/64922/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/64922/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2014-07-01","Children: Protection","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what recent assessment he has made of the adequacy of the UK's child protection legislation; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Glenda Jackson","Hampstead and Kilburn","Glenda Jackson","203198"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/64923","Department for Education","false","2014-07-10","<p> </p><p>The Government's position on the change in employer contribution rate for the Teachers' Pension Scheme was published in the Teachers' Pension Scheme Valuation Report (Actuarial Valuation as at 31 March 2012), which is available here:</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/324305/TPS_2012_valuation_report_FINAL_9_June_2014.pdf" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/324305/TPS_2012_valuation_report_FINAL_9_June_2014.pdf</a></p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The position for non-teaching staff is less clear-cut as they are covered by the Local Government Pension Scheme, which consists of around 90 different funds, and thus the change in employer costs as a result of recent reforms will vary from fund to fund.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The expected changes in National Insurance for employers as a result of moves to a single tier state pension were set out in the impact assessments for Pensions Act 2014, which are available here:</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/311316/pensions-act-ia-annex-a-single-tier-state-pension.pdf" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/311316/pensions-act-ia-annex-a-single-tier-state-pension.pdf</a></p><p> </p>","Yeovil","Mr David Laws",,"2014-07-10T16:27:37.1413152Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/64923/answer","Biography information for Mr David Laws","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/64923/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/64923/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2014-07-01","Schools: Finance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what assessment the Government has made of the impact on school budgets in 2016-17 of planned changes in pension and national insurance contributions.","false","Biography information for John Pugh","Southport","John Pugh","203204"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/64924","Department for Education","false","2014-07-07","<p>The Government is extending the entitlement criteria for two-year-old early learning. From September 2014, two-year-olds will be eligible if they have a current statement of special educational needs (SEN) or an education, health and care plan (EHCP) or if they get Disability Living Allowance. The Government is determined to ensure that all children are able to benefit from their government-funded early education, and local authorities have the necessary funding, including in the high-needs block of the dedicated schools grant, to secure this.</p><p> </p><p>The Government published Childcare and Early Years Survey of Parents 2012/13 in January 2014, which contains a range of information about the views of parents with disabled children about childcare. The survey contained information about access to childcare, including flexible and holiday care, the quality and affordability of this care. It is published online at: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/275992/SFR06-2014_Childcare_and_Early_Years_Survey_of_Parents_2012-13_final.pdf" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/275992/SFR06-2014_Childcare_and_Early_Years_Survey_of_Parents_2012-13_final.pdf</a></p><p> </p><p>The Government published Childcare and Early Years Providers Survey 2011, which contains information on early years providers who care for children with disabilities. This survey is published online at:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/childcare-and-early-years-providers-survey-2011" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/childcare-and-early-years-providers-survey-2011</a></p><p> </p>","South West Norfolk","Elizabeth Truss","203321","2014-07-07T10:22:39.4037248Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/64924/answer","Biography information for Elizabeth Truss","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/64924/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/64924/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2014-07-01","Children: Day Care","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what assessment he has made of the additional costs to (a) parents and (b) childcare providers of providing childcare for disabled children.","false","Biography information for Lucy Powell","Manchester Central","Lucy Powell","203315"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/64925","Department for Education","false","2014-07-07","<p>I have asked Ofsted to respond using the data they hold on registered nursery places. Sir Michael Wilshaw, Her Majesty's Chief Inspector will write to the Hon Lady, and a copy of his response has been placed in the House Libraries. Some providers such as schools with nursery provision for children aged three or over, are exempt from registration. The number of places therefore may not include the full range of early years provision available in the area.</p><p>The Department for Education's Childcare and Early Years Providers Survey[1] collects data on all registered childcare places, including those in maintained schools and nurseries. These figures are therefore more comprehensive than the Ofsted figures; however data is only available at a national and regional level, and in this case only for the North West.</p><p>[1]<a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/childcare-and-early-years-providers-survey-2011" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/childcare-and-early-years-providers-survey-2011</a></p>","South West Norfolk","Elizabeth Truss",,"2014-07-07T16:36:32.9082146Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/64925/answer","Biography information for Elizabeth Truss","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/64925/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/64925/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2014-07-01","Pre-school Education: Warrington","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, how many nursery places were available in (a) Warrington and (b) Warrington North constituency in each year since 1995-96.","false","Biography information for Helen Jones","Warrington North","Helen Jones","203327"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/64926","Department for Education","false","2014-07-07","<p>The Government is extending the entitlement criteria for two-year-old early learning. From September 2014, two-year-olds will be eligible if they have a current statement of special educational needs (SEN) or an education, health and care plan (EHCP) or if they get Disability Living Allowance. The Government is determined to ensure that all children are able to benefit from their government-funded early education, and local authorities have the necessary funding, including in the high-needs block of the dedicated schools grant, to secure this.</p><p> </p><p>The Government published Childcare and Early Years Survey of Parents 2012/13 in January 2014, which contains a range of information about the views of parents with disabled children about childcare. The survey contained information about access to childcare, including flexible and holiday care, the quality and affordability of this care. It is published online at: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/275992/SFR06-2014_Childcare_and_Early_Years_Survey_of_Parents_2012-13_final.pdf" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/275992/SFR06-2014_Childcare_and_Early_Years_Survey_of_Parents_2012-13_final.pdf</a></p><p> </p><p>The Government published Childcare and Early Years Providers Survey 2011, which contains information on early years providers who care for children with disabilities. This survey is published online at:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/childcare-and-early-years-providers-survey-2011" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/childcare-and-early-years-providers-survey-2011</a></p><p> </p>","South West Norfolk","Elizabeth Truss","203315","2014-07-07T10:22:39.4931061Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/64926/answer","Biography information for Elizabeth Truss","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/64926/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/64926/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2014-07-01","Children: Day Care","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what assessment he has made of the level of accessibility of childcare for disabled children; how many childcare settings of all types of provision provide places for disabled children; what proportion of disabled children are able to access early years provision; and how many disabled children access the free early years entitlement at (a) three and four years old and (b) two years old.","false","Biography information for Lucy Powell","Manchester Central","Lucy Powell","203321"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/64927","Department for Education","false","2014-07-08","<p>Staff passes of people who no longer work for the Department are required to be returned or deactivated.</p>","South West Norfolk","Elizabeth Truss",,"2014-07-08T15:40:36.7566111Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/64927/answer","Biography information for Elizabeth Truss","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/64927/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/64927/answer","South West Norfolk","Elizabeth Truss","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/64927/answer/previousversion/8590","Biography information for Elizabeth Truss","60","Education","Education","2014-07-01","Security","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, whether all employees of his Department are required to return their departmental pass when they cease working for his Department.","false","Biography information for Lisa Nandy","Wigan","Lisa Nandy","203339"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/64928","Department for Education","false","2014-07-07","<p>Data on the proportion of children made an offer of their first choice school for England has recently been published as part of the Statistical First Release âSecondary and primary school applications and offers: 2014'. This is published online:</p><p> </p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/statistics-school-applications" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/statistics-school-applications</a></p><p> </p>","Yeovil","Mr David Laws",,"2014-07-07T14:50:48.0630348Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/64928/answer","Biography information for Mr David Laws","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/64928/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/64928/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2014-07-01","Primary Education: Admissions","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what recent estimate he has made of the number of children in England starting primary school in September 2014 who have received a place at their first choice school.","false","Biography information for Steve McCabe","Birmingham, Selly Oak","Steve McCabe","203229"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/64929","Department for Education","false","2014-07-07","<p>To date, 99,755 children have taken part in the Challenge the Gap project.</p>","Yeovil","Mr David Laws",,"2014-07-07T14:53:45.8678599Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/64929/answer","Biography information for Mr David Laws","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/64929/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/64929/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2014-07-01","Pupils: Disadvantaged","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, how many children are involved in the Challenge the Gap scheme.","false","Biography information for Steve McCabe","Birmingham, Selly Oak","Steve McCabe","203230"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/64930","Department for Education","false","2014-07-07","<p>In its first two years, the Challenge the Gap programme has reached 150 schools, of which 84 are primary schools. 16 schools in Birmingham are involved in the programme, 11 of which are primary schools.</p>","Yeovil","Mr David Laws",,"2014-07-07T14:58:12.4818082Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/64930/answer","Biography information for Mr David Laws","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/64930/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/64930/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2014-07-01","Pupils: Disadvantaged","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, how many primary schools in (a) England and (b) Birmingham are taking part in the Challenge the Gap scheme.","false","Biography information for Steve McCabe","Birmingham, Selly Oak","Steve McCabe","203231"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/64931","Department for Education","false","2014-07-07","<p>Information on the number and percentage of pupils known to be eligible for and claiming free school meals in Warrington local authority and England for 2002 to 2014 has been placed in the House Library. Comparable data for earlier years are not available.</p><p>Information by parliamentary constituency is not published.</p><p> </p>","Yeovil","Mr David Laws",,"2014-07-07T14:54:55.4161514Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/64931/answer","Biography information for Mr David Laws","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/64931/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/64931/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2014-07-01","Free School Meals: Warrington","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, how many children in (a) Warrington and (b) Warrington North constituency received free school meals in each year since 1995-96.","false","Biography information for Helen Jones","Warrington North","Helen Jones","203252"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/64932","Department for Energy and Climate Change","false","2014-07-07","<p>The Department's latest assessment of the impact of the three Energy Company Obligation (ECO) targets on the number of households supported, energy company spending and number of measures installed is set out in the 5 March âThe Future of the Energy Company Obligation: Assessment of Impacts:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/286926/The_Future_of_the_Energy_Company_Obligation_Assessment_of_Impacts.pdf" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/286926/The_Future_of_the_Energy_Company_Obligation_Assessment_of_Impacts.pdf</a></p><p>The Department will be publishing a final assessment of the impact of the ECO policy to accompany the forthcoming response to the Government's consultation on the Future Of the Energy Company Obligation.</p><p> </p>","Bexhill and Battle","Gregory Barker","203282 ; 203284","2014-07-07T12:54:07.7016775Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/64932/answer","Biography information for Lord Barker of Battle","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/64932/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/64932/answer",,,,,"63","Energy and Climate Change","Energy and Climate Change","2014-07-01","Fuel Poverty","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Energy and Climate Change, what estimate his Department has made of the number of households who will receive assistance under (a) affordable warmth, (b) carbon savings community and (c) carbon saving target in (i) 2014-15, (ii) 2015-16 and (iii) 2016-17.","false","Biography information for Caroline Flint","Don Valley","Caroline Flint","203283"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/64933","Department for Energy and Climate Change","false","2014-07-09","<p>The Government is preparing proposals for a new fuel poverty strategy for England in line with the provisions of the Warm Homes and Energy Conservation Act 2000.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","Bexhill and Battle","Gregory Barker",,"2014-07-09T16:31:55.0852813Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/64933/answer","Biography information for Lord Barker of Battle","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/64933/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/64933/answer",,,,,"63","Energy and Climate Change","Energy and Climate Change","2014-07-01","Fuel Poverty","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Energy and Climate Change, when his Department will publish its fuel poverty strategy.","false","Biography information for Caroline Flint","Don Valley","Caroline Flint","203280"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/64934","Department for Energy and Climate Change","false","2014-07-08","<p>Cyber security is one of the Government's top four national security priorities. DECC is working with government departments and agencies, as well as with industry partners, to ensure that the risks to the energy sector are understood and that appropriate mitigations are established. It would not be appropriate to comment on specific cases.</p><p> </p>","Sevenoaks","Michael Fallon",,"2014-07-08T12:47:50.2640298Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/64934/answer","Biography information for Sir Michael Fallon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/64934/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/64934/answer",,,,,"63","Energy and Climate Change","Energy and Climate Change","2014-07-01","Energy: Cybercrime","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Energy and Climate Change, what assessment he has made of the extent to which the UK's energy infrastructure was exposed to the recent Energetic Bear cyberattack.","false","Biography information for Tom Blenkinsop","Middlesbrough South and East Cleveland","Tom Blenkinsop","203265"
