"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/64942","Department for Energy and Climate Change","false","2014-07-07","<p>The Department's latest assessment of the impact of the three Energy Company Obligation (ECO) targets on the number of households supported, energy company spending and number of measures installed is set out in the 5 March âThe Future of the Energy Company Obligation: Assessment of Impacts:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/286926/The_Future_of_the_Energy_Company_Obligation_Assessment_of_Impacts.pdf" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/286926/The_Future_of_the_Energy_Company_Obligation_Assessment_of_Impacts.pdf</a></p><p>The Department will be publishing a final assessment of the impact of the ECO policy to accompany the forthcoming response to the Government's consultation on the Future Of the Energy Company Obligation.</p><p> </p>","Bexhill and Battle","Gregory Barker","203283 ; 203284","2014-07-07T12:54:07.7954258Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/64942/answer","Biography information for Lord Barker of Battle","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/64942/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/64942/answer",,,,,"63","Energy and Climate Change","Energy and Climate Change","2014-07-01","Fuel Poverty","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Energy and Climate Change, what estimate his Department has made of the number of measures to be installed under (a) affordable warmth, (b) carbon savings community and (c) carbon saving target in (i) 2014-15, (ii) 2015-16 and (iii) 2016-17.","false","Biography information for Caroline Flint","Don Valley","Caroline Flint","203282"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/64943","Department for Energy and Climate Change","false","2014-07-09","<p>Up to Â£125 million was allocated to the Green Deal Cashback scheme and the Green Deal Home Improvement Fund (GDHIF).</p><p>At the end of May 2014* over Â£10m had been allocated to customers, of which Â£6.4m had been paid in Cashback payments following installation of 13,001 measures.</p><p>At the end of June 2014, the GDHIF had allocated Â£18 million.</p><p><em>*DECC statistics on Green Deal and ECO are published monthly at <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/green-deal-and-energy-company-obligation-eco-monthly-statistics-june-2014" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/green-deal-and-energy-company-obligation-eco-monthly-statistics-june-2014</a> </em></p><p><em>Figures to the end of June will be published in the next monthly release on 22 July</em></p><p> </p>","Bexhill and Battle","Gregory Barker",,"2014-07-09T16:37:30.8658616Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/64943/answer","Biography information for Lord Barker of Battle","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/64943/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/64943/answer",,,,,"63","Energy and Climate Change","Energy and Climate Change","2014-07-01","Green Deal Scheme","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Energy and Climate Change, how much funding has been (a) allocated and (b) spent on the Green Deal cashback incentive scheme to date.","false","Biography information for Caroline Flint","Don Valley","Caroline Flint","203289"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/64944","Department for Energy and Climate Change","false","2014-07-07","<p>DECC research has consistently shown that around four fifths of households that had a Green Deal assessment have installed, were in the process or intended to install at least one measure. Research published in March 2014, showed that 22% of households that had an installation after a Green Deal assessment were not thinking about installing that measure before they had an assessment. For those households that installed solid wall insulation 70% of them were not thinking about installing it before they had a Green Deal assessment.</p><p> </p>","Bexhill and Battle","Gregory Barker",,"2014-07-07T12:50:36.6092437Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/64944/answer","Biography information for Lord Barker of Battle","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/64944/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/64944/answer",,,,,"63","Energy and Climate Change","Energy and Climate Change","2014-07-01","Green Deal Scheme","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Energy and Climate Change, pursuant to the Answer of 19 June 2014, Official Report, column 1247, on energy efficiency, what the evidential basis is for the statement that Green Deal assessments are stimulating action on energy efficiency.","false","Biography information for Caroline Flint","Don Valley","Caroline Flint","203338"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/64945","Department for Energy and Climate Change","false","2014-07-09","<p> </p><p>The number of fuel poor households in England under the Low Income High Costs (LIHC) indicator of fuel poverty are available for the following years:</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td> </td><td><p><strong><em>Fuel poor households (millions)</em></strong></p></td><td><p><strong><em>Percentage of households fuel poor</em></strong></p></td><td><p><strong><em>Year on year percentage change</em></strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p><em>1996</em></p></td><td><p>2.68</p></td><td><p>13.7</p></td><td> </td></tr><tr><td><p><em>2003</em></p></td><td><p>2.44</p></td><td><p>11.8</p></td><td> </td></tr><tr><td><p><em>2004</em></p></td><td><p>2.49</p></td><td><p>11.9</p></td><td><p>2.1</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><em>2005</em></p></td><td><p>2.43</p></td><td><p>11.5</p></td><td><p>-2.6</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><em>2006</em></p></td><td><p>2.26</p></td><td><p>10.7</p></td><td><p>-6.8</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><em>2007</em></p></td><td><p>2.36</p></td><td><p>11.0</p></td><td><p>4.2</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><em>2008</em></p></td><td><p>2.44</p></td><td><p>11.4</p></td><td><p>3.5</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><em>2009</em></p></td><td><p>2.49</p></td><td><p>11.5</p></td><td><p>2.0</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><em>2010</em></p></td><td><p>2.47</p></td><td><p>11.5</p></td><td><p>-0.5</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><em>2011</em></p></td><td><p>2.39</p></td><td><p>10.9</p></td><td><p>-3.4</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><em>2012</em></p></td><td><p>2.28</p></td><td><p>10.4</p></td><td><p>-4.5</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p><strong> </strong></p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","Bexhill and Battle","Gregory Barker",,"2014-07-09T16:56:38.1618095Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/64945/answer","Biography information for Lord Barker of Battle","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/64945/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/64945/answer",,,,,"63","Energy and Climate Change","Energy and Climate Change","2014-07-01","Fuel Poverty","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Energy and Climate Change, pursuant to the Answer of 19 June 2014, Official Report, column 1252, on energy markets (competition), what estimate he has made of the level of fuel poverty under the low income high costs indicator in each year between 1997 and 2010.","false","Biography information for Caroline Flint","Don Valley","Caroline Flint","203336"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/64946","Department for Energy and Climate Change","false","2014-07-07","<p>In a competitive market, pricing decisions are a commercial matter for companies.</p><p>Consumers can put pressure on companies to reduce prices by switching to the best deal for them â Ofgem's Retail Market Reforms to deliver a simpler, clear market combined with Government's push to significantly reduce switching times and require suppliers to share consumer data with trusted third parties, should make this easier to do.</p><p>The Government supported Ofgem's recent move to write to the largest suppliers, challenging them to explain to consumers the impact of falling wholesale prices on their retail prices. Evidence that large suppliers raise prices more quickly when costs increase than they reduce prices when costs fall was one of the issues underpinning Ofgem's recent referral of the energy markets to the Competition and Markets Authority.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","Sevenoaks","Michael Fallon",,"2014-07-07T16:08:20.7543973Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/64946/answer","Biography information for Sir Michael Fallon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/64946/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/64946/answer",,,,,"63","Energy and Climate Change","Energy and Climate Change","2014-07-01","Energy: Prices","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Energy and Climate Change, what steps he is taking to reduce consumer energy prices in-line with changes in the wholesale market prices.","false","Biography information for Jim Shannon","Strangford","Jim Shannon","203217"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/64947","Department for Energy and Climate Change","false","2014-07-08","<p>In the answer I gave to the rt. hon. Member on 12<sup>th</sup> May 2014 (<em>Official Report, Column 344-5W)</em>, I confirmed that a copy of the Bloomberg New Energy Finance analysis of new investment in UK renewable electricity was placed in the Libraries of both Houses. This analysis shows that average annual investment in renewables has more than doubled in this Parliament, compared with the previous one.</p><p>I have today also placed the Bloomberg New Energy Finance analysis of new investment in renewable electricity in 2013 in the Libraries of both Houses. This shows that UK had the highest level of renewable investment in Europe in 2013.</p><table><tbody><tr><td> </td><td><p><strong>2013 (in $m)</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p><em>United Kingdom</em></p></td><td><p><strong>11,981</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p><em>Germany</em></p></td><td><p><strong>10,999</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p><em>Italy </em></p></td><td><p><strong> 3,563</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p><em>France</em></p></td><td><p><strong> 3,036</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p><em>Spain</em></p></td><td><p><strong> 580</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p><em>Other EU Europe</em></p></td><td><p><strong>11,900</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>TOTAL</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>42,059</strong></p></td></tr></tbody></table><p><em>Source: Bloomberg New Energy Finance</em></p><p> </p>","Sevenoaks","Michael Fallon","203382","2014-07-08T12:46:59.1935788Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/64947/answer","Biography information for Sir Michael Fallon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/64947/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/64947/answer",,,,,"63","Energy and Climate Change","Energy and Climate Change","2014-07-01","Renewable Energy","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Energy and Climate Change, pursuant to his contribution of 18 June 2014, Official Report, column 1191, on energy prices, what the evidential basis is for his statement that the UK had the highest level of renewable investment in Europe in 2013.","false","Biography information for Caroline Flint","Don Valley","Caroline Flint","203381"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/64948","Department for Energy and Climate Change","false","2014-07-08","<p>In the answer I gave to the rt. hon. Member on 12<sup>th</sup> May 2014 (<em>Official Report, Column 344-5W)</em>, I confirmed that a copy of the Bloomberg New Energy Finance analysis of new investment in UK renewable electricity was placed in the Libraries of both Houses. This analysis shows that average annual investment in renewables has more than doubled in this Parliament, compared with the previous one.</p><p>I have today also placed the Bloomberg New Energy Finance analysis of new investment in renewable electricity in 2013 in the Libraries of both Houses. This shows that UK had the highest level of renewable investment in Europe in 2013.</p><table><tbody><tr><td> </td><td><p><strong>2013 (in $m)</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p><em>United Kingdom</em></p></td><td><p><strong>11,981</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p><em>Germany</em></p></td><td><p><strong>10,999</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p><em>Italy </em></p></td><td><p><strong> 3,563</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p><em>France</em></p></td><td><p><strong> 3,036</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p><em>Spain</em></p></td><td><p><strong> 580</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p><em>Other EU Europe</em></p></td><td><p><strong>11,900</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>TOTAL</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>42,059</strong></p></td></tr></tbody></table><p><em>Source: Bloomberg New Energy Finance</em></p><p> </p>","Sevenoaks","Michael Fallon","203381","2014-07-08T12:46:59.1154426Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/64948/answer","Biography information for Sir Michael Fallon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/64948/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/64948/answer",,,,,"63","Energy and Climate Change","Energy and Climate Change","2014-07-01","Renewable Energy","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Energy and Climate Change, pursuant to his contribution of 18 June 2014, Official Report, column 1191, on energy prices, if he will place in the Library a copy of the Bloomberg new energy finance analysis.","false","Biography information for Caroline Flint","Don Valley","Caroline Flint","203382"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/64949","Department for Energy and Climate Change","false","2014-07-08","<p>The Government faces the challenge of securing up to Â£100bn on investment in electricity generation and networks by the end of the decade to keep the lights on and decarbonise energy, having already attracted Â£45bn since 2010. This is a higher level of investment than previously achieved, based on ONS investment data going back to 2004.</p><p> </p>","Sevenoaks","Michael Fallon",,"2014-07-08T16:19:03.0563713Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/64949/answer","Biography information for Sir Michael Fallon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/64949/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/64949/answer",,,,,"63","Energy and Climate Change","Energy and Climate Change","2014-07-01","Energy","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Energy and Climate Change, pursuant to his contribution of 18 June 2014, Official Report, column 1191, on energy prices, what the evidential basis is for his statement that there was under-investment in the UK's energy infrastructure.","false","Biography information for Caroline Flint","Don Valley","Caroline Flint","203383"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/64950","Department for Energy and Climate Change","false","2014-07-08","<p>Ofgem have carried out a detailed assessment of the rocket and feather effect. , first in a research paper in 2011 and more recently, along with the Competition and Markets Authority (CMA), in the State of the Market Assessment. Evidence that large suppliers raise prices more quickly when costs increase than they reduce prices when costs fall was one of the issues underpinning Ofgem's recent referral of the energy markets to the CMA.</p>","Sevenoaks","Michael Fallon",,"2014-07-08T12:45:53.9743216Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/64950/answer","Biography information for Sir Michael Fallon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/64950/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/64950/answer",,,,,"63","Energy and Climate Change","Energy and Climate Change","2014-07-01","Energy: Prices","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Energy and Climate Change, pursuant to his contribution of 18 June 2014, Official Report, column 1193, on energy prices, what assessment his Department has made of the rocket and feather effect in energy prices.","false","Biography information for Caroline Flint","Don Valley","Caroline Flint","203384"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/64951","Department for Energy and Climate Change","false","2014-07-09","<p>The latest research, with households that had an assessment between January and March 2014, found that the majority of households said they did not pay for their Green Deal assessment because the assessor company did not charge a fee. For those that paid for an assessment, the (mean) average cost was Â£157.</p><p> </p>","Bexhill and Battle","Gregory Barker","203367","2014-07-09T16:36:41.3429111Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/64951/answer","Biography information for Lord Barker of Battle","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/64951/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/64951/answer",,,,,"63","Energy and Climate Change","Energy and Climate Change","2014-07-01","Green Deal Scheme","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Energy and Climate Change, how many households have received free green deal assessments to date.","false","Biography information for Caroline Flint","Don Valley","Caroline Flint","203361"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/64952","Department for Energy and Climate Change","false","2014-07-03","<p>No estimate has been made of the number of landlords acting as a direct result of the provisions within the Energy Act 2011.</p><p> </p>","Bexhill and Battle","Gregory Barker",,"2014-07-03T15:53:15.4702816Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/64952/answer","Biography information for Lord Barker of Battle","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/64952/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/64952/answer",,,,,"63","Energy and Climate Change","Energy and Climate Change","2014-07-01","Private Rented Housing: Energy","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Energy and Climate Change, what estimate his Department has made of the number of landlords who have upgraded the energy efficiency of their properties to EPC rating E or higher in line with the Energy Act 2011 since the implementation of that Act.","false","Biography information for Caroline Flint","Don Valley","Caroline Flint","203362"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/64953","Department for Energy and Climate Change","false","2014-07-07","<p>The saving on energy bills from installing heating and insulation measures will depend on several factors including the particular measure, energy prices and household characteristics that affect their energy consumption.</p><p>DECC has estimated that households can save from around Â£25 to Â£270 or more per installation per year from installing the main insulation measures. This is based on estimated energy savings from an illustrative three bedroom semi-detached house. Further information on illustrative bill savings for different measures can be found in table 49 of the 2012 Final Green Deal and ECO IA:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/42984/5533-final-stage-impact-assessment-for-the-green-deal-a.pdf" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/42984/5533-final-stage-impact-assessment-for-the-green-deal-a.pdf</a>.</p><p> </p>","Bexhill and Battle","Gregory Barker",,"2014-07-07T12:51:50.1349085Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/64953/answer","Biography information for Lord Barker of Battle","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/64953/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/64953/answer",,,,,"63","Energy and Climate Change","Energy and Climate Change","2014-07-01","Housing: Energy","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Energy and Climate Change, what estimate his Department has made of the average annual saving to a household's energy bill from a (a) condensing gas boiler, (b) cavity wall insulation, (c) loft insulation, (d) solid wall insulation and (e) other forms of insulation.","false","Biography information for Caroline Flint","Don Valley","Caroline Flint","203363"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/64954","Department for Energy and Climate Change","false","2014-07-07","<p>The Department has not estimated the average savings on energy bills for households that have received measures specifically under the Energy Company Obligation. The saving on energy bills will depend on several factors including the particular measure installed, energy prices and household characteristics that affect their energy consumption.</p><p>However, more generally, DECC has estimated that households can save from around Â£25 to Â£270 or more per installation per year from installing the main insulation measures (e.g. loft, cavity and solid wall). This is based on estimated energy savings from an illustrative three bedroom semi-detached house (see 2012 Final Green Deal and ECO IA for details: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/42984/5533-final-stage-impact-assessment-for-the-green-deal-a.pdf" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/42984/5533-final-stage-impact-assessment-for-the-green-deal-a.pdf</a>).</p><p> </p>","Bexhill and Battle","Gregory Barker",,"2014-07-07T12:51:16.8044313Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/64954/answer","Biography information for Lord Barker of Battle","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/64954/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/64954/answer",,,,,"63","Energy and Climate Change","Energy and Climate Change","2014-07-01","Energy Companies Obligation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Energy and Climate Change, what estimate his Department has made of the average saving on energy bills for households that have received measures under the Energy Company Obligation.","false","Biography information for Caroline Flint","Don Valley","Caroline Flint","203366"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/64955","Department for Energy and Climate Change","false","2014-07-09","<p>The latest research, with households that had an assessment between January and March 2014, found that the majority of households said they did not pay for their Green Deal assessment because the assessor company did not charge a fee. For those that paid for an assessment, the (mean) average cost was Â£157.</p><p> </p>","Bexhill and Battle","Gregory Barker","203361","2014-07-09T16:36:41.452277Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/64955/answer","Biography information for Lord Barker of Battle","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/64955/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/64955/answer",,,,,"63","Energy and Climate Change","Energy and Climate Change","2014-07-01","Green Deal Scheme","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Energy and Climate Change, what estimate his Department has made of the average cost of a Green Deal assessment.","false","Biography information for Caroline Flint","Don Valley","Caroline Flint","203367"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/64956","Department for Energy and Climate Change","false","2014-07-03","<p>In the answer I gave to the rt. hon. Member on 12<sup>th</sup> May 2014 (<em>Official Report, Column 344-5W)</em>, I confirmed that a copy of the Bloomberg New Energy Finance analysis of new investment in UK renewable electricity was placed in the Libraries of both Houses. This analysis shows that average annual investment in renewables has more than doubled in this Parliament, compared with the previous one. When rounded, the figures also show a 20% increase in renewable electricity between 2012 and 2013.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","Bexhill and Battle","Gregory Barker","203377","2014-07-03T16:10:32.7586063Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/64956/answer","Biography information for Lord Barker of Battle","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/64956/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/64956/answer",,,,,"63","Energy and Climate Change","Energy and Climate Change","2014-07-01","Electricity","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Energy and Climate Change, pursuant to the Answer of 19 June 2014, Official Report, column 1249, on low-carbon electricity projects, what the evidential basis is for the statement of the Minister of State for Energy and Climate Change that investment in low-carbon electricity projects has doubled during the current Parliament.","false","Biography information for Caroline Flint","Don Valley","Caroline Flint","203376"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/64957","Department for Energy and Climate Change","false","2014-07-09","<p>All domestic energy efficiency initiatives are included within the overall Green Deal programme.</p><p>As part of the Autumn Statement in December 2013, the Government announced that Â£540m will be made available to support energy efficiency improvements over the next three years, of which Â£450m will support domestic installation of energy efficiency measures.</p><p>Â£150m has been allocated in 2014-15.</p><p>All further budget allocations will be made during the forthcoming Spending Review and DECC business planning exercises.</p><p> </p>","Bexhill and Battle","Gregory Barker",,"2014-07-09T11:01:35.6925965Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/64957/answer","Biography information for Lord Barker of Battle","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/64957/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/64957/answer",,,,,"63","Energy and Climate Change","Energy and Climate Change","2014-07-01","Housing: Energy","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Energy and Climate Change, what financial support his Department has planned to allocate to (a) the Green Deal and (b) other domestic energy efficiency programmes for expenditure in (i) 2014-15, (ii) 2015-16, (iii) 2016-17 and (iv) any subsequent years.","false","Biography information for Caroline Flint","Don Valley","Caroline Flint","203368"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/64958","Department for Energy and Climate Change","false","2014-07-03","<p>In the answer I gave to the rt. hon. Member on 12<sup>th</sup> May 2014 (<em>Official Report, Column 344-5W)</em>, I confirmed that a copy of the Bloomberg New Energy Finance analysis of new investment in UK renewable electricity was placed in the Libraries of both Houses. This analysis shows that average annual investment in renewables has more than doubled in this Parliament, compared with the previous one. When rounded, the figures also show a 20% increase in renewable electricity between 2012 and 2013.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","Bexhill and Battle","Gregory Barker","203376","2014-07-03T16:10:32.3367681Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/64958/answer","Biography information for Lord Barker of Battle","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/64958/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/64958/answer",,,,,"63","Energy and Climate Change","Energy and Climate Change","2014-07-01","Renewable Energy","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Energy and Climate Change, pursuant to the Answer of 19 June 2014, Official Report, column 1249, on low-carbon electricity projects, if he will place in the Library a copy of the Bloomberg analysis.","false","Biography information for Caroline Flint","Don Valley","Caroline Flint","203377"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/64959","Department for Energy and Climate Change","false","2014-07-09","<p>All domestic energy efficiency initiatives are included within the overall Green Deal programme.</p><ul><li>Â£67.4m was allocated in 2011-12.</li><li>Â£71.65m was allocated in 2012-13.</li><li>Â£200.1m was allocated in 2013-14.</li></ul><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","Bexhill and Battle","Gregory Barker",,"2014-07-09T11:14:17.6210298Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/64959/answer","Biography information for Lord Barker of Battle","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/64959/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/64959/answer",,,,,"63","Energy and Climate Change","Energy and Climate Change","2014-07-01","Housing: Energy","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Energy and Climate Change, what financial support his Department allocated to (a) the Green Deal and (b) other domestic energy efficiency programmes in (i) 2011-12, (ii) 2012-13 and (iii) 2013-14.","false","Biography information for Caroline Flint","Don Valley","Caroline Flint","203369"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/64960","Department for Energy and Climate Change","false","2014-07-09","<p>The Department's latest assessment of the impact of the Energy Company Obligation (ECO) on fuel poverty is set out in âThe Future of the Energy Company Obligation: Assessment of Impactsâ published in March 2014. This is available at:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/286926/The_Future_of_the_Energy_Company_Obligation_Assessment_of_Impacts.pdf" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/286926/The_Future_of_the_Energy_Company_Obligation_Assessment_of_Impacts.pdf</a></p><p> </p>","Bexhill and Battle","Gregory Barker","203365","2014-07-09T16:50:45.1320753Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/64960/answer","Biography information for Lord Barker of Battle","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/64960/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/64960/answer",,,,,"63","Energy and Climate Change","Energy and Climate Change","2014-07-01","Fuel Poverty","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Energy and Climate Change, how many households are forecast to be lifted from fuel poverty under the energy company obligation in each year between 2013 and 2017.","false","Biography information for Caroline Flint","Don Valley","Caroline Flint","203356"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/64961","Department for Energy and Climate Change","false","2014-07-07","<p>Previous DECC research has shown that around 1 in 10 households that have had a Green Deal assessment paid, at least in part, for it. However the latest DECC research, published in June 2014, showed that 14% of households paid, at least in part, towards an assessment. This research was carried out with households that had an assessment between 1January and 30 March 2014 and shows that the number of households paying for an assessment increased.</p><p> </p>","Bexhill and Battle","Gregory Barker",,"2014-07-07T12:54:55.2240848Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/64961/answer","Biography information for Lord Barker of Battle","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/64961/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/64961/answer",,,,,"63","Energy and Climate Change","Energy and Climate Change","2014-07-01","Green Deal Scheme","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Energy and Climate Change, what estimate his Department has made of the number of households that have paid for a Green Deal assessment to date.","false","Biography information for Caroline Flint","Don Valley","Caroline Flint","203370"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/64962","Department for Energy and Climate Change","false","2014-07-07","<p>The estimate of more than Â£45bn of electricity infrastructure investment between 2010 and 2013 is calculated by DECC based on modelling consistent with the EMR Delivery Plan.</p><p>The modelling suggests that since 2010, over Â£30bn has been invested in electricity generation capacity, principally in renewable technologies. In addition, since 2010, more than Â£16bn of investment has been made in electricity transmission and distribution.</p><p>Generation capacity investment levels are determined by multiplying capacity changes by a technology specific capital cost per unit of capacity value, which varies over time. A project's total investment cost is profiled over its construction lifetime, with total annual investment levels reflecting the sum of investment in that year across all technology types. All data on costs and profiles is taken from DECC's Electricity Generation Costs dataset.</p><p>Onshore and offshore transmission network investment estimates come from National Grid's networks module that has been added to DECC's dispatch model as part of the EMR Delivery Plan analysis.1 Network investment for onshore transmission owners is based on additions to network owners' regulated asset value under the price control periods consistent with National Grid's Gone Green scenario. From 2013 onwards Gone Green investment estimates are adjusted for different uptake of technologies in DECC's dispatch modelling.</p><p>Network investment for offshore transmission is calculated by using a relevant cost associated with Offshore Transmission Owners (OFTOs) based on an average cost per kW for known projects. This is multiplied by offshore wind capacity built.</p><p>Investment in distribution networks is based on additions to network owners' regulated asset value under the DPCR5 price control period.</p><p>Further detail on DECC's Electricity Generation Costs is available here: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/decc-electricity-generation-costs-2013" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/decc-electricity-generation-costs-2013</a></p><p> </p><p><em><strong>[1]</strong></em><em> Find further detail in the National Grid report: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/267614/Annex_D_-_National_Grid_EMR_Report.pdf" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/267614/Annex_D_-_National_Grid_EMR_Report.pdf</a></em></p>","Sevenoaks","Michael Fallon",,"2014-07-07T16:10:47.7183318Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/64962/answer","Biography information for Sir Michael Fallon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/64962/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/64962/answer",,,,,"63","Energy and Climate Change","Energy and Climate Change","2014-07-01","Electricity","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Energy and Climate Change, pursuant to the Answer of 19 June 2014, Official Report, column 1258, on energy security, on which process he calculated that there has been Â£45 billion of electricity investment since 2010.","false","Biography information for Caroline Flint","Don Valley","Caroline Flint","203378"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/64963","Department for Energy and Climate Change","false","2014-07-07","<p>Â£100 cashback is available for households that have a Green Deal assessment and install a measure via the Green Deal Home Improvement Fund route, however the scheme only recently launched and it is too early to give a figure on spend. Local authorities offered free Green Deal assessments from Green Deal Pioneer Places Fund and DECC estimates that 9,543 free assessments were funded through it. The Pioneer Places Fund of Â£10m was allocated to Local Authorities and/or consortia of Local Authorities in England to demonstrate ambitious approaches to kick starting local Green Deal activity in both the domestic and non-domestic sectors. As well as funding Green Deal assessments, activities that were supported by DECC funding included: piloting local marketing approaches, including a street by street approach to roll out, establishing a network of local Green Deal show homes, area wide events to publicise the Green Deal, working with local partners such as the local NHS to drive demand for the Green Deal and working with community and other civil society groups to deliver demand for the Green Deal.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","Bexhill and Battle","Gregory Barker",,"2014-07-07T12:53:12.8207194Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/64963/answer","Biography information for Lord Barker of Battle","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/64963/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/64963/answer",,,,,"63","Energy and Climate Change","Energy and Climate Change","2014-07-01","Green Deal Scheme","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Energy and Climate Change, how much his Department has spent on free Green Deal assessments for households to date.","false","Biography information for Caroline Flint","Don Valley","Caroline Flint","203371"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/64964","Department for Energy and Climate Change","false","2014-07-07","<p>As part of our evaluation of Green Deal and ECO we have commissioned a range of consumer research, covering research into the customer journey including people's views, attitudes and experiences of the Green Deal and ECO journeys, the experience of arranging assessments, actions and intentions after receipt of a Green Deal Advice Report and general public awareness of Green Deal. DECC has published the various outputs of this research on its website and will continue to do so in line with the Government Social Research publication guidance.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","Bexhill and Battle","Gregory Barker",,"2014-07-07T12:52:35.4377792Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/64964/answer","Biography information for Lord Barker of Battle","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/64964/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/64964/answer",,,,,"63","Energy and Climate Change","Energy and Climate Change","2014-07-01","Housing: Energy","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Energy and Climate Change, what consumer research his Department has commissioned on (a) the Green Deal and (b) the Energy Company Obligation since 2013.","false","Biography information for Caroline Flint","Don Valley","Caroline Flint","203372"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/64965","Department for Energy and Climate Change","false","2014-07-10","<p>The statement by my rt. hon. Friend the Secretary of State for Energy and Climate Change referred to the overall level of investment. Â£45 billion has been invested in electricity infrastructure since 2010. This figure was published in DECC's âEnergy Investment Reportâ April 20141, which also presented information from the ONS Annual Business Survey showing increased annual capital expenditure on electricity, power generation and distribution since 2005, with 2012 as the record year to date.</p><p>Since 2010 six gas plants have commissioned in the UK with a further Â£700m plant at Carrington under construction. This compares to five gas plants that commissioned from 2005 â 2010. Details of each plant are listed in the table below2. Additionally, energy companies will have developed and implemented investment plans in relation to their existing fleet of gas plants.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p><strong>Plant name</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Capacity (MW)</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Commission year</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Carrington</p></td><td><p>860</p></td><td><p>Under construction</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>West Burton</p></td><td><p>1300</p></td><td><p>2013</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Pembroke</p></td><td><p>2180</p></td><td><p>2012</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Langage</p></td><td><p>905</p></td><td><p>2010</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Severn</p></td><td><p>848</p></td><td><p>2010</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Grain</p></td><td><p>1320</p></td><td><p>2010</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Staythorpe C</p></td><td><p>1724</p></td><td><p>2010</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Marchwood</p></td><td><p>842</p></td><td><p>2009</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Little Barford GT</p></td><td><p>17</p></td><td><p>2006</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Coolkeeragh CCGT</p></td><td><p>408</p></td><td><p>2005</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Coolkeeragh OCGT</p></td><td><p>72</p></td><td><p>2005</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Wilton GT2</p></td><td><p>42</p></td><td><p>2005</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p><em><strong>[1]</strong></em><em><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/305860/DECC_Energy_investment_report_Web_Final.pdf" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/305860/DECC_Energy_investment_report_Web_Final.pdf</a></em></p><p> </p><p><em>2</em><em> Taken from DUKES Table 5.11 <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/electricity-chapter-5-digest-of-united-kingdom-energy-statistics-dukes" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/electricity-chapter-5-digest-of-united-kingdom-energy-statistics-dukes</a></em></p><p> </p>","Sevenoaks","Michael Fallon",,"2014-07-10T15:24:52.6915376Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/64965/answer","Biography information for Sir Michael Fallon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/64965/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/64965/answer",,,,,"63","Energy and Climate Change","Energy and Climate Change","2014-07-01","Natural Gas","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Energy and Climate Change, pursuant to the Answer of 19 June 2014, Official Report, column 1258, on energy security, what the evidential basis is for his statement that the rate of investment in gas is increasing.","false","Biography information for Caroline Flint","Don Valley","Caroline Flint","203379"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/64966","Department for Energy and Climate Change","false","2014-07-07","<p>We estimate that investment in new, cleaner energy infrastructure through the government's Electricity Market Reforms will help support up to 250,000 jobs by 2020. This reflects estimates of how many jobs could be supported by electricity generated using renewable, nuclear, and carbon capture and storage technologies, and includes jobs in the relevant supply chains.</p><p>In nuclear energy, we estimate there will be between 69,000 and 81,000 jobs by 2020. This is made up of 29,000-41,000 jobs across the nuclear supply chain at the peak of construction activity, from the 16GW of new build capacity industry is planning to build by 2030, in addition to the 40,000 people currently employed in nuclear energy.<sup>1</sup></p><p>We also estimate that up to 200,000 jobs could be supported in renewable electricity by 2020. This estimate is based on the Renewable Energy Association's estimate of employment in the sector in 2012/13<sup>2</sup>, and a range of possible deployment levels in 2020 as set out in the Government's Electricity Market Reform Delivery Plan.3</p><p>Within the carbon capture and storage sector, we estimate that around 8,000 jobs could be supported in the early stages of deployment by 2020.<sup>4</sup></p><p> </p><p> </p><p><em><strong>[1]</strong></em><em> The Economic Benefits of the UK's Nuclear Supply Chain Capabilities, Oxford Economics, 2013 (A report commissioned for DECC) <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/168017/bis-13-633-the-economic-benefit-of-improving-the-uk-nuclear-supply-chain-capabilities.pdf" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/168017/bis-13-633-the-economic-benefit-of-improving-the-uk-nuclear-supply-chain-capabilities.pdf</a></em></p><p> </p><p><em>2</em><em> REVIEW â Renewable Energy View 2013, Renewable Energy Association, April 2014 (<a href="http://www.r-e-a.net/resources/rea-publications" target="_blank">http://www.r-e-a.net/resources/rea-publications</a>).</em></p><p> </p><p><em>3</em><em> EMR Delivery Plan, DECC, 2013 (<a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/electricity-market-reform-delivery-plan" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/electricity-market-reform-delivery-plan</a>)</em></p><p> </p><p><em>4</em><em> DECC estimate DECC estimate based on AEA analysis â Assessing the domestic supply chain barriers to the commercial deployment of carbon capture and storage within the power sector (2013). <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/assessing-the-domestic-supply-chain-barriers-to-the-commercial-deployment-of-carbon-capture-and-storage-within-the-power-sector" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/assessing-the-domestic-supply-chain-barriers-to-the-commercial-deployment-of-carbon-capture-and-storage-within-the-power-sector</a></em></p><p> </p>","Sevenoaks","Michael Fallon",,"2014-07-07T16:06:01.2747367Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/64966/answer","Biography information for Sir Michael Fallon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/64966/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/64966/answer",,,,,"63","Energy and Climate Change","Energy and Climate Change","2014-07-01","Energy","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Energy and Climate Change, what the evidential basis is for the statement in paragraph 2.1 of his Departmental annual report 2013-14, HC9, published on 26 June 2014, that investment in cleaner energy infrastructure will help support up to 250,000 jobs by 2020.","false","Biography information for Paul Flynn","Newport West","Paul Flynn","203357"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/64967","Department for Energy and Climate Change","false","2014-07-03","<p>In the answer I gave to the rt. hon. Member on 12<sup>th</sup> May 2014 (<em>Official Report, Column 344-5W)</em>, I confirmed that a copy of the Bloomberg New Energy Finance analysis of new investment in UK renewable electricity was placed in the Libraries of both Houses. This shows that the investment rate is going up, with average annual investment in renewables more than doubling in this Parliament, compared with the previous one.</p><p> </p>","Sevenoaks","Michael Fallon",,"2014-07-03T16:12:21.3266303Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/64967/answer","Biography information for Sir Michael Fallon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/64967/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/64967/answer",,,,,"63","Energy and Climate Change","Energy and Climate Change","2014-07-01","Renewable Energy","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Energy and Climate Change, pursuant to the Answer of 19 June 2014, Official Report, column 1258, on energy security, what the evidential basis is for his statement that the rate of investment in renewables is increasing.","false","Biography information for Caroline Flint","Don Valley","Caroline Flint","203380"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/64968","Department for Energy and Climate Change","false","2014-07-09","<p>Based on the last parliamentary session, we estimate that 6,960 Ministerial replies are sent out from the Department of Energy and Climate Change to hon. Members. The time taken to establish what proportion of such replies are sent by a) letter, or b) email, would involve filtering down more specifically, and this would involve significant manual sifting of individual correspondence items and thus entail a disproportionate cost. However, we estimate that 98% of replies are sent by letter, as we only reply to Ministerial letters by e-mail on request from hon. Members, and we are rarely asked to do so.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","Bexhill and Battle","Gregory Barker",,"2014-07-09T12:46:47.3965019Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/64968/answer","Biography information for Lord Barker of Battle","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/64968/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/64968/answer",,,,,"63","Energy and Climate Change","Energy and Climate Change","2014-07-01","Members: Correspondence","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Energy and Climate Change, if he will estimate the total number of ministerial replies from his Department to hon. Members in a parliamentary session; and what proportion of such replies are sent (a) by letter and (b) by email.","false","Biography information for Simon Kirby","Brighton, Kemptown","Simon Kirby","203303"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/64969","Department for Energy and Climate Change","false","2014-07-09","<p>I am placing in the Libraries of the House a copy of the list of projects, as requested.</p><p> </p>","Bexhill and Battle","Gregory Barker",,"2014-07-09T16:51:17.4706617Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/64969/answer","Biography information for Lord Barker of Battle","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/64969/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/64969/answer",,,,,"63","Energy and Climate Change","Energy and Climate Change","2014-07-01","Renewable Energy","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Energy and Climate Change, with reference to the Answer of 17 June 2013, Official Report, column 461W, on renewable energy, UIN 159722, if he will place in the Library a copy of the list of projects recorded on the renewable energy planning database since 1 January 2010 with the potential to generate 20MW or more cross-referenced with information provided by developers.","false","Biography information for Caroline Flint","Don Valley","Caroline Flint","203340"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/64970","Department for Energy and Climate Change","false","2014-07-09","<p>The Department's latest assessment of the impact of the Energy Company Obligation (ECO) on fuel poverty is set out in âThe Future of the Energy Company Obligation: Assessment of Impactsâ published in March 2014. This is available at:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/286926/The_Future_of_the_Energy_Company_Obligation_Assessment_of_Impacts.pdf" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/286926/The_Future_of_the_Energy_Company_Obligation_Assessment_of_Impacts.pdf</a></p><p> </p>","Bexhill and Battle","Gregory Barker","203356","2014-07-09T16:50:45.3820558Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/64970/answer","Biography information for Lord Barker of Battle","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/64970/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/64970/answer",,,,,"63","Energy and Climate Change","Energy and Climate Change","2014-07-01","Energy Companies Obligation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Energy and Climate Change, how many households (a) in fuel poverty and (b) not in fuel poverty and (c) in total he expects to receive assistance under the energy company obligation in each year between 2013 and 2017.","false","Biography information for Caroline Flint","Don Valley","Caroline Flint","203365"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/64971","Department for Energy and Climate Change","false","2014-07-09","<p>Estimating the number of fuel poor households helped through the Energy Company Obligation (ECO) would require us to know the equivalised household income and modelled energy bill of every household receiving support through the scheme.</p><p>However, we anticipate a large number of fuel poor households have been assisted under ECO. This is because there is a strong correlation between the characteristics of fuel poor households and the eligibility criteria for help under ECO Affordable Warmth and the Carbon Saving Communities Obligation. Further, the policy's design provides incentives for support to be delivered to those facing the highest energy bills: when such households are on low incomes, there is a high chance they will be fuel poor.</p><p>We publish regular data on the number of households support by ECO, under each part of the scheme, as well as the number and type of measures delivered. We also publish data on the costs of measures under ECO. All of this data is available at:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/green-deal-and-energy-company-obligation-eco-statistics" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/green-deal-and-energy-company-obligation-eco-statistics</a>.</p><p>The Department will be publishing a final assessment of the impact of the ECO policy to accompany the forthcoming response to the Government's consultation on âThe Future of the Energy Company Obligationâ.</p><p> </p>","Bexhill and Battle","Gregory Barker",,"2014-07-09T16:52:46.2353614Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/64971/answer","Biography information for Lord Barker of Battle","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/64971/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/64971/answer",,,,,"63","Energy and Climate Change","Energy and Climate Change","2014-07-01","Energy Companies Obligation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Energy and Climate Change, how many households (a) in fuel poverty, (b) not in fuel poverty and (c) in total have received measures under the energy company obligation to date; and what the average cost per household under the scheme was.","false","Biography information for Caroline Flint","Don Valley","Caroline Flint","203364"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/64972","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2014-07-07","<p> </p><p>The UK Government is already playing a key role in tackling a number of issues raised in this report. For example, we are already pressing for an agreement under the UN Convention on the Law of the Sea on the conservation and sustainable use of biodiversity in areas beyond national jurisdiction, in ensuring implementation of UN Resolution 61/105 on sustainable fisheries, and in promoting action to combat illegal fishing. We are also working with partner countries in OSPAR on a range of environmental measures in the north-east Atlantic including a regional action plan to address marine litter.</p><p> </p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice",,"2014-07-07T14:29:32.0407351Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/64972/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/64972/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/64972/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2014-07-01","Environment Protection: Seas and Oceans","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what steps he plans to take to implement the recommendations in the Global Ocean Commission's report, From Decline to Recovery: A Rescue Package for the Global Ocean.","false","Biography information for Zac Goldsmith","Richmond Park","Zac Goldsmith","203414"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/64973","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2014-07-08","<p>I refer the hon. Member to the reply given by my Rt. Hon. Friend, the member for Horsham, Mr Maude, on Thursday 3 July: Official Report, column 5-6W.</p>","North Cornwall","Dan Rogerson","203528","2014-07-08T15:00:08.6930607Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/64973/answer","Biography information for Dan Rogerson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/64973/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/64973/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2014-07-01","Members: Correspondence","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, if he will estimate the total number of ministerial replies from his Department to hon. Members in a parliamentary session; and what proportion of such replies are sent (a) by letter and (b) by email.","false","Biography information for Simon Kirby","Brighton, Kemptown","Simon Kirby","203304"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/64974","Department for Energy and Climate Change","false","2014-07-08","<p>No applications have been received for hydraulic fracturing of shale gas in East Yorkshire. However, small scale testing to determine rock characteristics is planned; these are a routine part of oil and gas operations<em>.</em></p><p> </p>","Sevenoaks","Michael Fallon",,"2014-07-08T11:45:49.8902708Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/64974/answer","Biography information for Sir Michael Fallon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/64974/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/64974/answer",,,,,"63","Energy and Climate Change","Energy and Climate Change","2014-07-01","Fracking: East Yorkshire","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Energy and Climate Change, whether any fracking, or explorative work relating to fracking (a) is currently taking place and (b) has recently taken place in East Yorkshire, and where; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Sir Greg Knight","East Yorkshire","Sir Greg Knight","203258"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/64975","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2014-07-07","<p> </p><p>Defra does not hold information on employment figures for gamekeepers. There is no requirement for gamekeepers or employers of gamekeepers to report this information to Defra.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>It is for landowners and gamekeeping organisations to encourage more people to become gamekeepers. However, Defra invests in a range of rural skills and jobs through initiatives under the Rural Development Programme for England.</p><p> </p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice","203213","2014-07-07T14:47:45.2212708Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/64975/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/64975/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/64975/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2014-07-01","Gamekeepers","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what steps his Department is taking to encourage more people to become gamekeepers.","false","Biography information for Jim Shannon","Strangford","Jim Shannon","203212"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/64976","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2014-07-07","<p> </p><p>Defra does not hold information on employment figures for gamekeepers. There is no requirement for gamekeepers or employers of gamekeepers to report this information to Defra.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>It is for landowners and gamekeeping organisations to encourage more people to become gamekeepers. However, Defra invests in a range of rural skills and jobs through initiatives under the Rural Development Programme for England.</p><p> </p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice","203212","2014-07-07T14:47:45.0806448Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/64976/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/64976/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/64976/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2014-07-01","Gamekeepers","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, how many people have become gamekeepers in each of the last three years; and what the age group and gender is of all registered gamekeepers.","false","Biography information for Jim Shannon","Strangford","Jim Shannon","203213"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/64977","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2014-07-07","<p> </p><p>As the independent economic regulator for the water sector, it is OFWAT's duty to review water prices every five years. This includes assessing the investment and pricing proposals included in water company business plans before setting limits on what companies can charge their customers. Most company business plans are proposing flat or declining customer bills from 2015.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>OFWAT has a rolling programme of activity to keep under review issues relating to affordability and it publishes analysis in this area. OFWAT is guided in its work by Defra's Strategic Policy Statement, published in May 2013, which sets out the policy framework within which the water regulator must operate and it identifies tackling affordability pressures as a key priority. OFWAT is required to monitor the action taken by water companies to help customers who struggle to afford their bills and report on this to the Secretary of State annually.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The Government has published guidance to water companies on the introduction of social tariffs, to assist them in providing support to customers at risk of affordability problems. The Government encourages water companies to introduce social tariffs to help vulnerable customers, taking account of local circumstances, needs and views.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>Defra is currently working with OFWAT and the Environment Agency to assess the long term affordability of water bills. This work will incorporate the outcomes of OFWAT's current review of water prices, which concludes in December 2014, and will report in 2015.</p><p> </p>","North Cornwall","Dan Rogerson","203253 ; 203320","2014-07-07T14:06:00.4889975Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/64977/answer","Biography information for Dan Rogerson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/64977/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/64977/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2014-07-01","Water Charges","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what work his Department has done to assess the long term effect of investment and pricing decisions made by (a) his Department, (b) OFWAT and (c) water companies on affordability for consumers; and if he will publish all such work.","false","Biography information for Maria Eagle","Garston and Halewood","Maria Eagle","203319"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/64978","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2014-07-07","<p> </p><p>As the independent economic regulator for the water sector, it is OFWAT's duty to review water prices every five years. This includes assessing the investment and pricing proposals included in water company business plans before setting limits on what companies can charge their customers. Most company business plans are proposing flat or declining customer bills from 2015.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>OFWAT has a rolling programme of activity to keep under review issues relating to affordability and it publishes analysis in this area. OFWAT is guided in its work by Defra's Strategic Policy Statement, published in May 2013, which sets out the policy framework within which the water regulator must operate and it identifies tackling affordability pressures as a key priority. OFWAT is required to monitor the action taken by water companies to help customers who struggle to afford their bills and report on this to the Secretary of State annually.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The Government has published guidance to water companies on the introduction of social tariffs, to assist them in providing support to customers at risk of affordability problems. The Government encourages water companies to introduce social tariffs to help vulnerable customers, taking account of local circumstances, needs and views.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>Defra is currently working with OFWAT and the Environment Agency to assess the long term affordability of water bills. This work will incorporate the outcomes of OFWAT's current review of water prices, which concludes in December 2014, and will report in 2015.</p><p> </p>","North Cornwall","Dan Rogerson","203253 ; 203319","2014-07-07T14:06:00.2546926Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/64978/answer","Biography information for Dan Rogerson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/64978/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/64978/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2014-07-01","Water Charges","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what guidance he has produced on how his Department, OFWAT and water companies should monitor and assess affordability for consumers when carrying out their functions.","false","Biography information for Maria Eagle","Garston and Halewood","Maria Eagle","203320"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/64979","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2014-07-08","<p> </p><p>I refer the Rt. Hon. Member to the reply given on Monday, 07 July 2014: Official Report, Column 73W.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>An example of a policy intervention where the reduction of risk of death is valued is in the consultation stage Impact Assessment on whether to issue a Ministerial Direction for the preparation of Reservoir Flood Plans, issued on 17 December 2009. This document has been placed in the House Library.</p><p> </p>","North Cornwall","Dan Rogerson",,"2014-07-08T14:51:22.9869856Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/64979/answer","Biography information for Dan Rogerson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/64979/answer","Reservoir Flood Plans - PQ 0237.doc","Reservoir Flood Plans - PQ 0237.doc","Document to go to Library - answer UIN203288","Document to go to Library - answer UIN203288","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/64979/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2014-07-01","Policy","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, at what level his Department values the reduction of the risk of death per fatal casualty prevented; and if he will give an example of a policy intervention where this evaluation was made.","false","Biography information for Mr Stephen O'Brien","Eddisbury","Mr Stephen O'Brien","203288"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/64980","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2014-07-08","<p> </p><p>Since its launch in October 2012, the Dairy Code of Conduct has helped to improve contractual relationships between farmers and their milk buyers. The Code was developed by the industry and now covers more than 85% of domestic milk production. I regularly discuss the Code with industry.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>I am aware of some concerns that exist about the notice periods for farmers where there are any price changes and how these apply to dairy co-operatives. I have emphasised that any difficulties or suggestions for improving the Code should be raised with the Rt Hon. Alex Fergusson, MSP who is currently leading an independent review process.</p><p> </p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice",,"2014-07-08T13:23:28.1961028Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/64980/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/64980/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/64980/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2014-07-01","Dairy Farming","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, how many complaints his Department has received on the Dairy Code of Conduct.","false","Biography information for Simon Hart","Carmarthen West and South Pembrokeshire","Simon Hart","203268"
